"{\"key\":\"pattern-router-pattern-for-multi-platform-installers-1-thin-route\",\"type\":\"pattern\",\"content\":\"Router pattern for multi-platform installers: (1) thin routers parse flags and validate platform, (2) construct installer path with validated platform name, (3) verify installer exists in expected directory via realpath + regex, (4) source (not exec) platform-specific installer for better error handling. Backwards compatible: defaults to claude when no platform flag provided.\",\"source\":\"user\",\"tags\":[\"pattern\",\"pattern\",\"route\",\"error\"],\"ts\":1771039170,\"bead\":\"bdcompound-7h4\"}"
"{\"key\":\"pattern-security-hardening-for-conversion-scripts-requires-1-path\",\"type\":\"pattern\",\"content\":\"Security hardening for conversion scripts requires: (1) path validation with relative() check, (2) 10MB file size limit, (3) YAML SAFE_SCHEMA usage, (4) template syntax escaping, (5) explicit file permissions 644/755, (6) model name allowlist, (7) exact dependency pinning (no ^ or ~).\",\"source\":\"user\",\"tags\":[\"pattern\",\"api\",\"security\",\"ui\",\"model\",\"schema\",\"validation\"],\"ts\":1771038599,\"bead\":\"bdcompound-18w\"}"
"{\"key\":\"pattern-typescript-plugin-pattern-for-opencode-1-bun-spawn-not\",\"type\":\"pattern\",\"content\":\"TypeScript plugin pattern for OpenCode: (1) Bun.spawn() not $ template for security, (2) pre-fork regex filtering before subprocess for performance, (3) Claude Code stdin JSON format for shell script compatibility, (4) absolute path validation for CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR.\",\"source\":\"user\",\"tags\":[\"pattern\",\"security\",\"performance\",\"pattern\",\"validation\",\"typescript\"],\"ts\":1771035049,\"bead\":\"bdcompound-18w\"}"
"{\"key\":\"pattern-use-opencode-s-shell-env-hook-to-set-claude-project-dir-glob\",\"type\":\"pattern\",\"content\":\"Use OpenCode's shell.env hook to set CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR globally instead of exporting per-script-call. This ensures all bd commands run by the agent also get the right project context.\",\"source\":\"user\",\"tags\":[\"pattern\",\"env\"],\"ts\":1771032070,\"bead\":\"bdcompound-a3a\"}"
"{\"key\":\"pattern-user-prefers-to-review-commits-before-pushing-ask-before-gi\",\"type\":\"pattern\",\"content\":\"User prefers to review commits before pushing. Ask before git commit and git push, don't do automatically.\",\"source\":\"user\",\"tags\":[\"pattern\"],\"ts\":1771035779,\"bead\":\"bdcompound-18w\"}"
{"key":"pattern-troubleshooting-docs-should-provide-copy-paste-commands-for","type":"pattern","content":"Troubleshooting docs should provide copy-paste commands for each platform with expected outputs, not just descriptions of what to check.","source":"user","tags":["pattern"],"ts":1771093043,"bead":"bdcompound-5j5"}
{"key":"learned-opencode-uses-typescript-plugin-system-with-event-hooks-she","type":"learned","content":"OpenCode uses TypeScript plugin system with event hooks (shell.env, session.created, tool.execute.after) not shell scripts in settings.json. Plugin loading shows console.log messages.\" && bd close bdcompound-rm9","source":"user","tags":["learned","env","typescript"],"ts":1771094262,"bead":"bdcompound-rm9"}
{"key":"learned-opencode-project-install-puts-plugin-ts-at-plugins-beads-com","type":"learned","content":"OpenCode project install puts plugin.ts at plugins/beads-compound/plugin.ts (not .opencode/plugins/). Commands/agents/skills/hooks go in .opencode/ subdirectories.\" && bd close bdcompound-mtf","source":"user","tags":["learned","go"],"ts":1771094373,"bead":"bdcompound-mtf"}
{"key":"fact-opencode-plugin-directory-structure-documented-at-https-op","type":"fact","content":"OpenCode plugin directory structure documented at https://opencode.ai/docs/plugins/ - plugins must be in .opencode/plugins/ subdirectory, not at project root.","source":"user","tags":["fact"],"ts":1771094687,"bead":"bdcompound-6b4"}
{"key":"pattern-platform-specific-converted-files-should-never-be-in-git-t","type":"pattern","content":"Platform-specific converted files should never be in git - they're build artifacts generated from source during installation. Only track source files in plugins/beads-compound/{commands,agents,skills,hooks}/","source":"user","tags":["pattern","ui"],"ts":1771094839,"bead":"bdcompound-zx5"}
{"key":"pattern-build-artifacts-opencode-gemini-vs-source-files-opencod","type":"pattern","content":"Build artifacts (opencode/ gemini/) vs source files (opencode-src/ gemini-src/) must be in separate directories. Source files tracked in git, build artifacts gitignored and generated at install time.","source":"user","tags":["pattern","ui"],"ts":1771099917,"bead":"bdcompound-ovn"}
{"key":"pattern-when-build-artifacts-are-gitignored-ci-workflows-must-expli","type":"pattern","content":"When build artifacts are gitignored, CI workflows must explicitly generate them before running tests or verification steps that depend on them.","source":"user","tags":["pattern","test","ui"],"ts":1771100218,"bead":"bdcompound-pwz"}
{"key":"learned-gemini-conversion-correctly-preserves-arguments-inside-cod","type":"learned","content":"Gemini conversion correctly preserves \\$ARGUMENTS inside code blocks while converting to {{args}} outside. Test was incorrectly failing because it checked for complete absence of \\$ARGUMENTS. Fixed to check for presence of #{{args}} instead.\" && bd close bdcompound-xhi","source":"user","tags":["learned","test","fix"],"ts":1771100443,"bead":"bdcompound-xhi"}
{"key":"pattern-for-dotfiles-compatibility-hook-paths-in-settings-json-shou","type":"pattern","content":"For dotfiles compatibility, hook paths in settings.json should use ~ expansion instead of absolute paths, allowing symlinked directories to work across machines.","source":"user","tags":["pattern"],"ts":1771124043,"bead":"bdcompound-0rm"}
{"key":"pattern-for-portable-dotfiles-global-install-must-be-self-contained","type":"pattern","content":"For portable dotfiles, global install must be self-contained - copy all required scripts, don't rely on external source paths. Marketplace installs bundle everything in plugin directory automatically.","source":"user","tags":["pattern","ui"],"ts":1771124538,"bead":"bdcompound-ayk"}
{"key":"learned-created-beads-recall-command-as-lightweight-utility-disabl","type":"learned","content":"Created /beads-recall command as lightweight utility (disable-model-invocation: true) that wraps recall.sh script with smart argument parsing. Supports 6 modes: stats, recent N, topic BEAD_ID, bead ID recall (extracts title as keywords), keyword search, and empty (shows usage). Added as new 'Knowledge Access' category in README separate from 'Saving Progress' since it's about retrieval not capture.","source":"user","tags":["learned","model","go"],"ts":1771185975,"bead":"bdcompound-gq4"}
{"key":"pattern-new-commands-should-follow-beads-prefix-if-they-re-part-of","type":"pattern","content":"New commands should follow beads- prefix if they're part of core workflow, no prefix for utilities. Command categories in README: Planning & Discovery, Executing Work, Reviewing & Quality, Saving Progress, Knowledge Access, Utility. Use disable-model-invocation: true for lightweight lookups that don't need complex reasoning.","source":"user","tags":["pattern","fix","model","go"],"ts":1771185980,"bead":"bdcompound-gq4"}
{"key":"decision-command-name-is-beads-design-clean-descriptive-follows-b","type":"decision","content":"Command name is /beads-design. Clean, descriptive, follows beads-* naming convention.\nArchitecture is delegation -- orchestrator calls existing /beads-brainstorm, /beads-plan, /beads-deepen, /beads-plan-review in sequence. Zero code duplication. Updates to individual commands automatically propagate.\nSmart pauses -- interactive brainstorm phase, auto-run plan, pause to confirm plan before deepen, then auto-chain deepen + plan-review.\nPhase gates with recovery -- each phase runs its existing verification. On failure, pause and offer retry/skip/abort.\nAuto-apply safe feedback from plan-review. Only pause for trade-off decisions requiring user judgment.\nDefault to Comprehensive detail level (user can override). This command is for the full thorough pipeline.\nNo skip flags. Auto-detect existing brainstorm context from bead ID. Keep the interface simple.\nPATTERN: Follows /lfg precedent for compound commands that chain multiple steps.\nFACT: Parallelism is preserved from existing commands -- each already maximally parallel internally (deepen spawns 20-40+ agents, plan-review runs 4 agents concurrently). Model hints (haiku/sonnet/opus) inherited.\nFACT: Output style is progress banners at phase transitions + clear verification status per phase + final consolidated summary with epic bead ID, child bead count, decisions captured, and review findings.","source":"user","tags":["decision","ui","pattern","convention","architecture","model","decision","retry"],"ts":1772853830,"bead":"bdcompound-8nm\nbdcompound-8nm\nbdcompound-8nm\nbdcompound-8nm\nbdcompound-8nm\nbdcompound-8nm\nbdcompound-8nm\nbdcompound-8nm\nbdcompound-8nm\nbdcompound-8nm"}
{"key":"learned-npx-smoke-tests-need-conditional-bd-install-step-same-patte","type":"learned","content":"npx smoke tests need conditional bd install step (same pattern as test-installation job) — bd not in CI by default\nPATTERN: execFileSync with array args prevents shell injection entirely — use instead of execSync with template strings for any user-controlled input\nCommand counts must be consistent across README, CATALOG, plugin.json description, pre-release-check.sh, and CI yaml — update all 5 locations when adding commands","source":"user","tags":["learned","test","pattern","job"],"ts":1773268657,"bead":"bdcompound-807\nbdcompound-807\nbdcompound-807"}
{"key":"decision-extracted-args-find-result-to-positional-variable-to-avoi","type":"decision","content":"Extracted args.find() result to _positional variable to avoid double evaluation; paths starting with '-' remain unsupported (acceptable edge case for CLI usage)\nAdded exitCode parameter to usage() defaulting to 1; --help callers pass 0 explicitly — cleaner than duplicating print logic\nFACT: Math.max(0, rows - 3) prevents negative contentHeight; also replaced magic +20 scroll buffer with Math.max(contentHeight * 4, 80) so long descriptions scale with terminal size\nPATTERN: Always quote \\$GITHUB_WORKSPACE in shell steps — self-hosted runners may have spaces in workspace paths\nAdded --provenance and --access public to npm publish; added id-token: write permission for SLSA provenance attestation","source":"user","tags":["decision","test","pattern"],"ts":1773269508,"bead":"bdcompound-807.9\nbdcompound-807.15\nbdcompound-807.17\nbdcompound-807.10\nbdcompound-807.12"}
{"key":"decision-fact-already-resolved-in-wave-1-via-positional-extraction","type":"decision","content":"FACT: Already resolved in Wave 1 via _positional extraction in bdcompound-807.9 fix — single args.find() call\nSet timeout: 30000 (30s) to match plan-view.js pattern but longer since export is a one-shot operation not interactive\nFACT: Already resolved in Wave 1 — replaced contentHeight+20 with Math.max(contentHeight*4, 80) so buffer scales with terminal size\nPinned to bun 1.3.6 (current installed version) and setup-bun@v2; this is a build-only tool so minor version drift risk is low but pinning is good hygiene","source":"user","tags":["decision","ui","fix","pattern","timeout","go"],"ts":1773269560,"bead":"bdcompound-807.16\nbdcompound-807.13\nbdcompound-807.18\nbdcompound-807.14"}
{"key":"decision-removed-process-on-exit-cleanup-all-exit-paths-sigi","type":"decision","content":"Removed process.on('exit', cleanup) — all exit paths (SIGINT, SIGTERM, 'q' key) already call cleanup() explicitly before process.exit(); the handler was a redundant double-call\nbd close bdcompound-807.19","source":"user","tags":["decision"],"ts":1773269577,"bead":"bdcompound-807.19\nbd close bdcompound-807.19"}
{"key":"learned-when-command-counts-change-update-claude-md-claude-rules","type":"learned","content":"When command counts change, update CLAUDE.md, .claude/rules/plugin-catalog.md, .claude-plugin/marketplace.json, README.md, plugin.json, pre-release-check.sh, and CI YAML (8 locations total). CLAUDE.md and plugin-catalog.md were missed this cycle.","source":"user","tags":["learned"],"ts":1773270461,"bead":"bdcompound-807"}
{"key":"decision-restored-process-on-exit-cleanup-as-defensive-practice","type":"decision","content":"Restored process.on('exit', cleanup) as defensive practice. Investigation showed die() calls all happen before setRawMode(true) in current code (buildTree runs at line 474, setRawMode at 487), so no current terminal corruption. However the handler is a zero-cost safety net for future code changes that might call die() after raw mode is active. Prior removal was based on correct analysis but removed a valuable defensive layer.","source":"user","tags":["decision","ui","rest"],"ts":1773270579,"bead":"bdcompound-807.20"}
{"key":"decision-removed-continue-on-error-true-the-conditional-guard-ha","type":"decision","content":"Removed continue-on-error: true — the conditional guard handles beads unavailability; continue-on-error on top was silencing real failures. Conditional guard = skip when unavailable. No continue-on-error = fail when available but broken.","source":"user","tags":["decision","error"],"ts":1773271253,"bead":"bdcompound-807.21"}
{"key":"decision-raised-bdexecfile-timeout-from-10000ms-to-30000ms-to-match-p","type":"decision","content":"Raised bdExecFile timeout from 10000ms to 30000ms to match plan-export.js. The failure mode in plan-view (silent empty string) is worse than plan-export (explicit error), so if anything plan-view needs the longer timeout more. Both tools call the same bd binary on the same data.","source":"user","tags":["decision","error","timeout"],"ts":1773271264,"bead":"bdcompound-807.25"}
{"key":"decision-updated-opencode-gemini-thresholds-in-pre-release-check-sh-f","type":"decision","content":"Updated OpenCode/Gemini thresholds in pre-release-check.sh from 25 to 29 to match CI verify-release job. Both files have SYNC: comments — they must always match. The Cortex threshold was left at 25 because CI does not check Cortex outputs in verify-release.","source":"user","tags":["decision","job"],"ts":1773271271,"bead":"bdcompound-807.24"}
{"key":"decision-updated-command-counts-to-29-in-claude-md-2-places-plugin","type":"decision","content":"Updated command counts to 29 in CLAUDE.md (2 places), plugin-catalog.md (header + 3 missing entries added), and marketplace.json description. Also added beads-design, beads-quick, beads-import to plugin-catalog.md table.","source":"user","tags":["decision","ui"],"ts":1773271329,"bead":"bdcompound-807.26"}
{"key":"decision-added-cortex-command-count-check-29-to-verify-release-j","type":"decision","content":"Added Cortex command count check (>= 29) to verify-release job to match pre-release-check.sh. Added --frozen-lockfile to bun install in verify-release for reproducibility. Both changes sync the CI gate with the local pre-release script.","source":"user","tags":["decision","job"],"ts":1773271971,"bead":"bdcompound-807.28"}
{"key":"investigation-plan-deepened-with-research-from-7-agents-4-research-3-rev","type":"investigation","content":"Plan deepened with research from 7 agents (4 research, 3 review). Key improvements: (1) Config moved from .beads/memory/ to .beads/config/ due to merge=union corruption risk, (2) Bead .5 rescoped from filesystem scanning to config-based injection due to security/complexity concerns, (3) Review Context must use XML wrapping to prevent prompt injection, (4) Cross-check validation scoped to warnings-only with high-value checks","source":"user","tags":["investigation","security","validation","config"],"ts":1773328774,"bead":"bdcompound-9f5"}
{"key":"decision-store-config-in-beads-config-project-setup-md-not-beads-me","type":"decision","content":"Store config in .beads/config/project-setup.md not .beads/memory/. Reason: .beads/memory/ uses merge=union gitattributes which would corrupt YAML frontmatter during git merges. .beads/config/ provides clean separation (memory=knowledge, config=settings).","source":"user","tags":["decision","config"],"ts":1773328776,"bead":"bdcompound-9f5.1"}
{"key":"decision-dropped-filesystem-scanning-of-claude-agents-and-claude","type":"decision","content":"Dropped filesystem scanning of ~/.claude/agents/ and .claude/agents/ for dynamic agent discovery. Reasons: (1) CRITICAL security risk - arbitrary .md files injected into prompts, (2) ~/.claude/agents/ writable by any process including malicious npm postinstall, (3) YAGNI - no current user complaint. Rescoped to: read project-setup config and inject Review Context into subagent prompts.","source":"user","tags":["decision","security","config"],"ts":1773328779,"bead":"bdcompound-9f5.5"}
{"key":"fact-yaml-parser-ts-line-15-has-a-bug-yamlload-core-schema-is-un","type":"fact","content":"yaml-parser.ts line 15 has a bug: yamlLoad.CORE_SCHEMA is undefined (yamlLoad is a function, not an object). This causes silent fallback to DEFAULT_SCHEMA which allows !!js/function tags. Fix: import CORE_SCHEMA directly from js-yaml. This is a pre-existing bug, not part of this epic, but should be fixed.","source":"user","tags":["fact","bug","fix","schema"],"ts":1773328782,"bead":"bdcompound-9f5.1"}
{"key":"learned-plan-review-second-pass-found-1-p1-critical-yaml-parser-c","type":"learned","content":"Plan review (second pass) found 1 P1 critical (yaml-parser CORE_SCHEMA bug), 8 important suggestions, 4 minor. Key structural changes: merge .5 into .2, drop .6 or extract to orchestrator, simplify .1 (no profiles/monorepo/version), simplify .3 Sources (freeform list). Protected artifacts need 6 locations updated, not 1.","source":"user","tags":["learned","bug","schema"],"ts":1773332707,"bead":"bdcompound-9f5"}
{"key":"decision-applied-plan-review-feedback-14-recommendations-11-applied","type":"decision","content":"Applied plan review feedback. 14 recommendations: 11 applied across 6 beads, 2 structural (close .5, close .6), 1 new bead (.9 for component counts). Key changes: merged .5 into .2, dropped .6, simplified .1 (no profiles/monorepo/version), simplified .3 Sources (freeform list), added agent allowlist to .2, added PR field sanitization to .7, added dedup note to .8.","source":"user","tags":["decision"],"ts":1773341546,"bead":"bdcompound-9f5"}
{"key":"decision-sources-section-added-as-freeform-bullet-list-in-epic-descri","type":"decision","content":"Sources section added as freeform bullet list in epic description template with explicit Brainstorm: entry type; child beads get a References subsection (subset of epic sources relevant to that child). Cross-check step 5.5 placed between bead creation and final review as warning-only with AskUserQuestion gate — does not block submission.","source":"user","tags":["decision"],"ts":1773341823,"bead":"bdcompound-9f5.3"}
{"key":"decision-project-setup-skill-md-uses-disable-model-invocation-true-an","type":"decision","content":"project-setup SKILL.md uses disable-model-invocation:true and XML critical_sequence tags (matching beads-knowledge pattern) so the agent follows a strict ordered flow: check existing -> detect stack -> select agents -> optional context -> write config. This matches the existing skill conventions.","source":"user","tags":["decision","pattern","convention","model","config"],"ts":1773341871,"bead":"bdcompound-9f5.1"}
{"key":"learned-beads-config-provisioning-belongs-in-the-memory-setup-step","type":"learned","content":".beads/config/ provisioning belongs in the memory setup step ([3/9]) of install-claude.sh, not as a separate step. Both memory and config are .beads/ subdirs provisioned at install time, so grouping them keeps the step count clean and the logic cohesive.","source":"user","tags":["learned","config"],"ts":1773341878,"bead":"bdcompound-9f5.1"}
{"key":"decision-agent-uses-a-four-step-orm-agnostic-algorithm-detect-orm","type":"decision","content":"Agent uses a four-step ORM-agnostic algorithm (detect ORM → list migrations → list schema artifacts → cross-reference) rather than ORM-specific top-level logic, so future ORM adapters can be added without changing the core flow.","source":"user","tags":["decision","adapter","migration","schema","go"],"ts":1773341891,"bead":"bdcompound-9f5.7"}
{"key":"learned-drizzle-s-out-directory-is-configurable-via-drizzle-config-t","type":"learned","content":"Drizzle's out directory is configurable via drizzle.config.ts — agent must parse the config file to find the actual migration path rather than hardcoding 'drizzle/', otherwise detection silently misses all migration files.","source":"user","tags":["learned","migration","config"],"ts":1773341897,"bead":"bdcompound-9f5.7"}
{"key":"decision-used-anchor-tag-reference-brainstorm-detected-within-the","type":"decision","content":"Used anchor-tag reference (#brainstorm-detected) within the decision tree to avoid repeating the 'what to do when found' block — keeps the three detection paths (label, recent keyword, old keyword) DRY while each path clearly jumps to the same handler","source":"user","tags":["decision","decision"],"ts":1773342037,"bead":"bdcompound-9f5.4"}
{"key":"learned-label-based-detection-must-check-both-the-input-bead-and-its","type":"learned","content":"Label-based detection must check both the input bead AND its parent — when planning a phase from a brainstorm epic, the input bead is a child (phase), not the brainstorm itself; the brainstorm label lives on the parent epic","source":"user","tags":["learned"],"ts":1773342043,"bead":"bdcompound-9f5.4"}
{"key":"decision-migration-drift-detector-added-as-agent-15-alongside-data-mi","type":"decision","content":"migration-drift-detector added as agent 15 alongside data-migration-expert (13) and deployment-verification-agent (14) in the conditional agents section. The two migration agents have a clear division: data-migration-expert owns migration CODE correctness, migration-drift-detector owns schema/migration CONSISTENCY. Trigger conditions expanded from Rails-only to all 5 ORM patterns (Rails, Alembic, Prisma, Drizzle, Knex) plus schema artifact paths. Dedup note added to Step 2 of Finding Synthesis to warn that both agents flag migration files and findings should be deduplicated.","source":"user","tags":["decision","pattern","migration","schema","deploy"],"ts":1773342058,"bead":"bdcompound-9f5.8"}
{"key":"decision-beads-parallel-injects-review-context-into-all-3-agent-promp","type":"decision","content":"beads-parallel injects review_context into all 3 agent prompt templates (standard, ralph, teams) under '## Project Conventions' — empty string when config missing, so no behavioral change for projects without project-setup.md","source":"user","tags":["decision","convention","config"],"ts":1773342083,"bead":"bdcompound-9f5.2"}
{"key":"learned-beads-review-md-already-had-migration-drift-detector-wired-a","type":"learned","content":"beads-review.md already had migration-drift-detector wired as a conditional agent (not in original bead scope) — allowlist was updated to reflect all 15 actual review agents, not the 14 documented in memory","source":"user","tags":["learned","migration"],"ts":1773342086,"bead":"bdcompound-9f5.2"}
{"key":"fact-component-counts-updated-to-29-agents-15-review-and-16-ski","type":"fact","content":"Component counts updated to 29 agents (15 review) and 16 skills after landing migration-drift-detector agent and project-setup skill. Six files updated: plugin.json, marketplace.json, plugin-catalog.md, pre-release-check.sh, CLAUDE.md, installers/install-claude.sh.","source":"user","tags":["fact","migration"],"ts":1773342196,"bead":"bdcompound-9f5.9"}
{"key":"learned-bd-create-title-component-knowledge-section-descripti","type":"learned","content":"bd create --title=\"Component: Knowledge section\" --description=\"$(cat <<'DESC\nMemory system demonstration with side-by-side terminals.\n\n## Layout\n- py-32, zinc-950 background\n- Title: \"Compounding memory\" text-5xl zinc-50\n- Side-by-side TerminalMockup components\n\n## Terminal Pair\nprefix, ~8-10 lines of curated output showing knowledge being captured during work\n- Right terminal: \"Recall\" -- shows the same knowledge being automatically recalled three weeks later in a new session, ~8-10 lines\n- Terminals side by side on desktop, stacked on mobile\n\n## Closing Line\n- \"Hit the same problem next month? Your agent already knows the fix.\n- text-xl zinc-400, centered below terminals\n\n## Files\n- Create: site/src/components/Knowledge.astro\n\n## Dependencies\n- Depends on: Infrastructure bead\n- Depends on: TerminalMockup component\n\n## Validation\n- Two terminals render side by side on desktop\n- Mobile: terminals stack vertically\n- Terminal content is readable and tells the capture->recall story\n- Closing line renders below\nDESC\n)\" --type=task --priority=2 --parent=bdcompound-hm0","source":"user","tags":["learned","layout","fix","validation"],"ts":1773708457,"bead":"bd create --title=\"Component: Knowledge section\" --description=\"$(cat <<'DESC'\nMemory system demonstration with side-by-side terminals.\n\n## Layout\n- py-32, zinc-950 background\n- Title: \"Compounding memory\" text-5xl zinc-50\n- Side-by-side TerminalMockup components\n\n## Terminal Pair\nwith\n- Right terminal: \"Recall\" -- shows the same knowledge being automatically recalled three weeks later in a new session, ~8-10 lines\n- Terminals side by side on desktop, stacked on mobile\n\n## Closing Line\n- \"Hit the same problem next month? Your agent already knows the fix.\"\n- text-xl zinc-400, centered below terminals\n\n## Files\n- Create: site/src/components/Knowledge.astro\n\n## Dependencies\n- Depends on: Infrastructure bead\n- Depends on: TerminalMockup component\n\n## Validation\n- Two terminals render side by side on desktop\n- Mobile: terminals stack vertically\n- Terminal content is readable and tells the capture->recall story\n- Closing line renders below\nDESC\n)\" --type=task --priority=2 --parent=bdcompound-hm0"}
{"key":"fact-fontsource-packages-for-geist-are-fontsource-geist-sans-and","type":"fact","content":"Fontsource packages for Geist are @fontsource/geist-sans and @fontsource/geist-mono (not @fontsource/geist). Original plan had wrong package names.","source":"user","tags":["fact"],"ts":1773708981,"bead":"bdcompound-hm0"}
{"key":"decision-research-conflict-resolved-stagger-pattern-research-show","type":"decision","content":"Research conflict resolved -- stagger pattern. Research showed data-reveal-delay attributes cannot be used in CSS calc() cross-browser. Updated to inline --index custom property pattern: style='--index: N' + calc(var(--index) * 80ms).","source":"user","tags":["decision","pattern"],"ts":1773708982,"bead":"bdcompound-hm0"}
{"key":"decision-research-conflict-resolved-tailwind-integration-use-tai","type":"decision","content":"Research conflict resolved -- Tailwind integration. Use @tailwindcss/vite as Vite plugin, NOT @astrojs/tailwind (deprecated for TW4). Import syntax is @import 'tailwindcss' not @tailwind directives.","source":"user","tags":["decision","deprecat"],"ts":1773708985,"bead":"bdcompound-hm0"}
{"key":"decision-plan-revised-after-research-changes-1-font-package-names","type":"decision","content":"Plan revised after research. Changes: (1) font package names corrected, (2) stagger pattern changed from data attributes to --index custom property, (3) easing updated to (0.22,1,0.36,1), (4) accessibility: no-motion-first + noscript fallback added, (5) copy button UX enhanced with 1500ms checkmark + aria-label states + localStorage persistence, (6) tab default changed to npx (most recognized), (7) SEO requirements added (JSON-LD, OG image), (8) counter animation clarified as @property + JS play-state hybrid.","source":"user","tags":["decision","ui","pattern"],"ts":1773708989,"bead":"bdcompound-hm0"}
{"key":"learned-bd-update-bdcompound-hm0-6-d-cat-desc-memory-system-d","type":"learned","content":"bd update bdcompound-hm0.6 -d \"$(cat <<'DESC\nMemory system demonstration with side-by-side terminals.\n\n## Layout\n- py-32, zinc-950 background\n- Title: \"Compounding memory\" text-5xl zinc-50\n- Side-by-side TerminalMockup components\n- data-reveal on terminal pair (below-fold section)\n\n## Terminal Pair\nprefix, ~8-10 lines of curated output\n- Right terminal: title \"Recall\" -- shows same knowledge recalled three weeks later, ~8-10 lines\n- Terminals side by side on desktop (grid-cols-2 gap-8), stacked on mobile\n- Images for knowledge section: agent-with-memory.jpg committed to site/src/assets/ (use Astro <Image> for optimization)\n\n## Closing Line\n- \"Hit the same problem next month? Your agent already knows the fix.\n- text-xl zinc-400, centered below terminals\n\n## Files\n- Create: site/src/components/Knowledge.astro\n- Add: site/src/assets/agent-with-memory.jpg (compressed <100KB before commit)\n\n## Dependencies\n- Depends on: Infrastructure bead (bdcompound-hm0.1)\n- Depends on: TerminalMockup component (bdcompound-hm0.2)\n\n## Validation\n- Two terminals render side by side on desktop\n- Mobile: terminals stack vertically\n- Terminal content tells the capture->recall story\n- Image renders via Astro <Image> with WebP/AVIF\n- Closing line renders below\nDESC\n)","source":"user","tags":["learned","layout","fix","validation"],"ts":1773709558,"bead":"bd update bdcompound-hm0.6 -d \"$(cat <<'DESC'\nMemory system demonstration with side-by-side terminals.\n\n## Layout\n- py-32, zinc-950 background\n- Title: \"Compounding memory\" text-5xl zinc-50\n- Side-by-side TerminalMockup components\n- data-reveal on terminal pair (below-fold section)\n\n## Terminal Pair\nwith\n- Right terminal: title \"Recall\" -- shows same knowledge recalled three weeks later, ~8-10 lines\n- Terminals side by side on desktop (grid-cols-2 gap-8), stacked on mobile\n- Images for knowledge section: agent-with-memory.jpg committed to site/src/assets/ (use Astro <Image> for optimization)\n\n## Closing Line\n- \"Hit the same problem next month? Your agent already knows the fix.\"\n- text-xl zinc-400, centered below terminals\n\n## Files\n- Create: site/src/components/Knowledge.astro\n- Add: site/src/assets/agent-with-memory.jpg (compressed <100KB before commit)\n\n## Dependencies\n- Depends on: Infrastructure bead (bdcompound-hm0.1)\n- Depends on: TerminalMockup component (bdcompound-hm0.2)\n\n## Validation\n- Two terminals render side by side on desktop\n- Mobile: terminals stack vertically\n- Terminal content tells the capture->recall story\n- Image renders via Astro <Image> with WebP/AVIF\n- Closing line renders below\nDESC\n)\""}
{"key":"decision-plan-reviewed-and-locked-9-child-beads-review-findings-ar","type":"decision","content":"Plan reviewed and locked. 9 child beads. Review findings: architecture(0H/4M/6L), simplicity(2H/1M/2L), security(0H/3M/4L), performance(2H/1M/3L). Auto-applied: 14 safe fixes. User-decided: cut counter animation, cut localStorage, move to local image assets, defer deployment bead. All beads updated with research+review findings.","source":"user","tags":["decision","security","performance","fix","architecture","deploy"],"ts":1773709591,"bead":"bdcompound-hm0"}
{"key":"learned-astro-components-with-slots-work-cleanly-for-terminal-chrome","type":"learned","content":"Astro components with slots work cleanly for terminal chrome wrappers -- the slot receives raw HTML content and the component handles all chrome styling. Using arbitrary Tailwind values like bg-[#ef4444] for the traffic light dots avoids needing to extend the theme config.","source":"user","tags":["learned","config"],"ts":1773710204,"bead":"bdcompound-hm0.2"}
{"key":"learned-astro-site-uses-tailwind-v4-with-theme-directive-for-custom","type":"learned","content":"Astro site uses Tailwind v4 with @theme directive for custom tokens (bg, surface, border, text, accent). The data-reveal system in Base.astro uses a shared IntersectionObserver -- components just add data-reveal attribute to opt in. No per-component JS needed.","source":"user","tags":["learned"],"ts":1773710236,"bead":"bdcompound-hm0.4"}
{"key":"learned-pipeline-component-uses-tailwind-v4-theme-tokens-bg-bg-te","type":"learned","content":"Pipeline component uses Tailwind v4 @theme tokens (bg-bg, text-accent, border-border, etc.) and the global data-reveal IntersectionObserver with --index CSS custom property for stagger delays. No separate observer needed per component.","source":"user","tags":["learned"],"ts":1773710240,"bead":"bdcompound-hm0.5"}
{"key":"learned-astro-inline-scripts-in-installcta-use-typed-record-for-tab","type":"learned","content":"Astro inline scripts in InstallCta use typed Record for tab-to-command mapping with in-memory state only (no localStorage). Copy button uses innerHTML swap for icon changes with setTimeout restore. Tab aria-selected and class toggling handled manually via classList add/remove.","source":"user","tags":["learned","timeout","rest"],"ts":1773710277,"bead":"bdcompound-hm0.7"}
{"key":"learned-hero-section-uses-no-data-reveal-attribute-to-ensure-immedia","type":"learned","content":"Hero section uses NO data-reveal attribute to ensure immediate LCP paint. Terminal mockup is hidden on mobile via hidden lg:block on the perspective-transform wrapper, keeping mobile payload light while desktop gets the tilted 3D terminal effect.","source":"user","tags":["learned"],"ts":1773710400,"bead":"bdcompound-hm0.3"}
{"key":"learned-terminalmockup-uses-a-plain-slot-with-no-wrapper-term","type":"learned","content":"TerminalMockup uses a plain <slot /> with no wrapper -- terminal content lines should use <p> tags with <span> color classes rather than <pre> blocks to stay consistent with the component's leading-relaxed styling","source":"user","tags":["learned"],"ts":1773710418,"bead":"bdcompound-hm0.6"}
{"key":"learned-cd-users-rbm-documents-projects-beads-compound-plugin","type":"learned","content":"cd /Users/rbm/Documents/projects/beads-compound-plugin && \\\ncommand-map iframe height needs calc(100dvh - 64px) to account for the 64px Nav bar. Using 100dvh without subtraction causes content to overflow below the viewport.\" && \\\ngit add site/src/pages/index.astro site/src/pages/command-map.astro && \\\ngit commit -m \"$(cat <<'EOF\nfeat(bdcompound-hm0.8): assemble index.astro + update command-map\n\n- Compose all 7 section components into index.astro\n- Wrap command-map in Base layout with shared Nav\n- Add iframe sandbox, adjust height for 64px nav bar\nEOF\n)","source":"user","tags":["learned","layout"],"ts":1773710492,"bead":"cd /Users/rbm/Documents/projects/beads-compound-plugin && \\\nbdcompound-hm0.8\ngit add site/src/pages/index.astro site/src/pages/command-map.astro && \\\ngit commit -m \"$(cat <<'EOF'\nfeat(bdcompound-hm0.8): assemble index.astro + update command-map\n\n- Compose all 7 section components into index.astro\n- Wrap command-map in Base layout with shared Nav\n- Add iframe sandbox, adjust height for 64px nav bar\nEOF\n)\""}
{"key":"decision-model-profile-wired-as-prose-instructions-in-command-md-fil","type":"decision","content":"model_profile wired as prose instructions in command .md files (not code), since commands are markdown processed by Claude agents. Critical agents annotated with '-- add model: opus if profile=quality' inline at each Task() dispatch site.","source":"user","tags":["decision","model"],"ts":1773788233,"bead":"bdcompound-jts"}
{"key":"fact-critical-agents-are-security-sentinel-architecture-strategi","type":"fact","content":"Critical agents are security-sentinel, architecture-strategist, goal-verifier, performance-oracle. Affected commands: lavra-review (3 agents), lavra-eng-review (3 agents), lavra-work single-bead (goal-verifier), lavra-work multi-bead Phase M8 (goal-verifier), lavra-ship (goal-verifier). lavra-design calls lavra-eng-review as a subcommand so it inherits automatically.","source":"user","tags":["fact","security","performance","architecture","go"],"ts":1773788234,"bead":"bdcompound-jts"}
{"key":"decision-replaced-150-line-bead-description-cap-with-completeness-gat","type":"decision","content":"Replaced 150-line bead description cap with completeness gate (all required sections present, zero judgment calls for the agent) and ~1000 LOC scope budget per bead. Rationale: agents drift when specs are vague, not when specs are long. Inspired by Mario Zechner's observations on agent-driven coding.","source":"user","tags":["decision","ui","rationale"],"ts":1773796119,"bead":"bdcompound-0pe"}
{"key":"decision-added-no-parallel-flag-to-lavra-work-non-default-opt-in","type":"decision","content":"Added --no-parallel flag to /lavra-work (non-default, opt-in). When set, overrides max_parallel_agents to 1 and pauses for user review between each bead. Rationale: the bottleneck is review quality, not code generation speed.","source":"user","tags":["decision","rationale"],"ts":1773796125,"bead":"bdcompound-0pe"}
{"key":"decision-added-prompt-injection-defense-to-knowledge-system-matching","type":"decision","content":"Added prompt injection defense to knowledge system matching config file treatment -- sanitize on read (strip role prefixes, bidirectional chars), wrap in untrusted-knowledge XML tags, grep -iF for search. Shell injection was already blocked by jq escaping and CSV import.","source":"user","tags":["decision","api","fix","config","rust"],"ts":1773797110,"bead":"bdcompound-dnv"}
{"key":"fact-bd-create-title-capture-astro-6-glob-loader-id-normalizat","type":"fact","content":"bd create --title=\"Capture Astro 6 glob loader ID normalization as FACT\" --type=task --priority=3 --parent=bdcompound-7ji --description=\"## What\n\nAdd a FACT knowledge entry documenting how Astro 6's glob loader normalizes collection entry IDs.\n\n## Context\n\nDiscovered during docs sidebar fix (commit 824ca14). The sidebar was showing empty Configuration and Releases sections because the section slugs used uppercase names like 'AUTONOMOUS_EXECUTION' and 'releases/v0.7.0', but Astro 6's glob loader normalizes IDs to lowercase and also strips dots from the path (not just the .md extension).\n\nExamples:\n- AUTONOMOUS_EXECUTION.md → id: autonomous_execution\n- COST.md → id: cost\n- releases/v0.7.0.md → id: releases/v070 (dots stripped from the whole id, not just extension)\n\nThis is different from what the code comments said ('Astro 5 glob loader uses id (filename without extension)') — the dot-stripping behavior is Astro 6-specific and undocumented.\n\n## What\n\nRun this command to add the knowledge entry:\n\n\\`\\`\\`bash\nAstro 6 glob loader normalizes collection entry IDs: lowercased + dots stripped (not just .md extension). UPPERCASE.md → uppercase. releases/v0.7.0.md → releases/v070. Section slug arrays in Doc.astro and index.astro must use lowercase ids with underscores (not hyphens) matching the loader output. Discovered when sidebar showed empty Configuration/Releases sections.\\\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n## Decisions\n\n### Locked\n- Entry type must be FACT (hard constraint about Astro 6 behavior, not a design choice)\n- Tags should include: astro, docs, sidebar, glob-loader\n\n### Discretion\n- Wording of the entry\n\n## Testing\n- [ ] Entry appears in \\`recall.sh \\\"astro\\\"\\` output\n- [ ] Entry type is fact\n\n## Validation\n- [ ] \\`bd comments add\\` command runs without error\n- [ ] Entry is searchable via recall.sh\n\n## Files\n- .beads/memory/knowledge.jsonl (written by hook automatically)\n\n## Dependencies\nNone — standalone knowledge capture","source":"user","tags":["fact","test","fix","decision","constraint","validation","error","config"],"ts":1773854276,"bead":"bd create --title=\"Capture Astro 6 glob loader ID normalization as FACT\" --type=task --priority=3 --parent=bdcompound-7ji --description=\"## What\n\nAdd a FACT knowledge entry documenting how Astro 6's glob loader normalizes collection entry IDs.\n\n## Context\n\nDiscovered during docs sidebar fix (commit 824ca14). The sidebar was showing empty Configuration and Releases sections because the section slugs used uppercase names like 'AUTONOMOUS_EXECUTION' and 'releases/v0.7.0', but Astro 6's glob loader normalizes IDs to lowercase and also strips dots from the path (not just the .md extension).\n\nExamples:\n- AUTONOMOUS_EXECUTION.md → id: autonomous_execution\n- COST.md → id: cost\n- releases/v0.7.0.md → id: releases/v070 (dots stripped from the whole id, not just extension)\n\nThis is different from what the code comments said ('Astro 5 glob loader uses id (filename without extension)') — the dot-stripping behavior is Astro 6-specific and undocumented.\n\n## What\n\nRun this command to add the knowledge entry:\n\n\\`\\`\\`bash\nbdcompound-7ji\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n## Decisions\n\n### Locked\n- Entry type must be FACT (hard constraint about Astro 6 behavior, not a design choice)\n- Tags should include: astro, docs, sidebar, glob-loader\n\n### Discretion\n- Wording of the entry\n\n## Testing\n- [ ] Entry appears in \\`recall.sh \\\"astro\\\"\\` output\n- [ ] Entry type is fact\n\n## Validation\n- [ ] \\`bd comments add\\` command runs without error\n- [ ] Entry is searchable via recall.sh\n\n## Files\n- .beads/memory/knowledge.jsonl (written by hook automatically)\n\n## Dependencies\nNone — standalone knowledge capture\""}
{"key":"pattern-bd-create-title-add-pattern-entry-config-security-bounda","type":"pattern","content":"bd create --title=\"Add PATTERN entry: config/security boundary doctrine\" --type=task --priority=3 --parent=bdcompound-7ji --description=\"## What\n\nAdd a PATTERN knowledge entry consolidating the config/security boundary doctrine that was established across ~9 decision entries this week but never captured as a single searchable PATTERN.\n\n## Context\n\nThe doctrine was established across beads bdcompound-9f5, bdcompound-dnv, and others:\n- Where data lives: .beads/config/ for settings (not .beads/memory/ — merge=union corrupts YAML)\n- How agent context injection works safely: XML wrapping + role prefix sanitization + bidirectional char stripping\n- How knowledge search is done safely: grep -iF (fixed-string) not grep -i (regex — metachar injection risk)\n- Security model: anything auto-injected into agent context is untrusted, must be sanitized and tagged\n\nThe pattern is settled doctrine. It should be one searchable entry, not 9 scattered decisions.\n\n## What\n\nRun this command:\n\n\\`\\`\\`bash\nConfig/security boundary doctrine for Lavra. (1) Storage: .beads/config/ for settings, .beads/memory/ for knowledge — never mix them, merge=union in memory/ corrupts YAML frontmatter. (2) Agent context injection: always XML-wrap with <untrusted-knowledge> tag + strip role prefixes (SYSTEM:/ASSISTANT:/[INST]) + strip bidirectional override chars + strip null bytes before injection. (3) Safe search: grep -iF (fixed-string) not grep -i — prevents metacharacter injection from knowledge content. Applies to: auto-recall.sh, any new hook that reads .beads/ content.\\\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n## Decisions\n\n### Locked\n- Entry type must be PATTERN\n- Must cover all three aspects: storage separation, injection sanitization, safe search\n\n### Discretion\n- Exact wording\n\n## Testing\n- [ ] \\`recall.sh \\\"security boundary\\\"\\` returns this entry\n- [ ] \\`recall.sh \\\"config memory\\\"\\` returns this entry\n- [ ] Entry type is pattern\n\n## Validation\n- [ ] Single entry replaces the need to search 9 decision entries for this doctrine\n- [ ] Tags include: security, config, p","source":"user","tags":["pattern","security","test","fix","pattern","model","decision","validation","config","rust"],"ts":1773854289,"bead":"bd create --title=\"Add PATTERN entry: config/security boundary doctrine\" --type=task --priority=3 --parent=bdcompound-7ji --description=\"## What\n\nAdd a PATTERN knowledge entry consolidating the config/security boundary doctrine that was established across ~9 decision entries this week but never captured as a single searchable PATTERN.\n\n## Context\n\nThe doctrine was established across beads bdcompound-9f5, bdcompound-dnv, and others:\n- Where data lives: .beads/config/ for settings (not .beads/memory/ — merge=union corrupts YAML)\n- How agent context injection works safely: XML wrapping + role prefix sanitization + bidirectional char stripping\n- How knowledge search is done safely: grep -iF (fixed-string) not grep -i (regex — metachar injection risk)\n- Security model: anything auto-injected into agent context is untrusted, must be sanitized and tagged\n\nThe pattern is settled doctrine. It should be one searchable entry, not 9 scattered decisions.\n\n## What\n\nRun this command:\n\n\\`\\`\\`bash\nbdcompound-7ji\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n## Decisions\n\n### Locked\n- Entry type must be PATTERN\n- Must cover all three aspects: storage separation, injection sanitization, safe search\n\n### Discretion\n- Exact wording\n\n## Testing\n- [ ] \\`recall.sh \\\"security boundary\\\"\\` returns this entry\n- [ ] \\`recall.sh \\\"config memory\\\"\\` returns this entry\n- [ ] Entry type is pattern\n\n## Validation\n- [ ] Single entry replaces the need to search 9 decision entries for this doctrine\n- [ ] Tags include: security, config, pattern, injection, sanitization\n\n## Files\n- .beads/memory/knowledge.jsonl (written by hook automatically)\n\n## Dependencies\nNone\""}
{"key":"investigation-bd-create-title-fix-pattern-type-gap-add-guidance-to-use","type":"investigation","content":"bd create --title=\"Fix PATTERN type gap: add guidance to use PATTERN: prefix explicitly\" --type=task --priority=4 --parent=bdcompound-7ji --description=\"## What\n\nAdd a PATTERN knowledge entry (and update CLAUDE.md guidance if appropriate) about when to use PATTERN: type explicitly vs burying patterns in DECISION/LEARNED entries.\n\n## Context\n\nThe retro found 0 explicit PATTERN: type entries this week despite 7 entries auto-tagged 'pattern' from content. The tags come from keyword detection in memory-capture.sh, but the entry type stayed 'decision' or 'learned'. This makes it harder to filter patterns specifically and defeats the purpose of having distinct knowledge types.\n\nThe six types each have a purpose:\n- LEARNED: insight from debugging/surprise behavior — one-time discovery\n- DECISION: what was chosen and why — specific choice with rationale\n- FACT: hard constraint, version req, environment detail — static truth\n- PATTERN: recurring convention or idiom — should be reused everywhere\nroot cause analysis\n- DEVIATION: auto-fix outside bead scope\n\nWhen something is worth reusing as a convention (not just recording a one-time choice), it should be PATTERN.\n\n## What\n\n1. Add this as a PATTERN entry itself:\n\n\\`\\`\\`bash\nbd comments add bdcompound-7ji \\\"PATTERN: Use PATTERN: type when capturing something meant to be reused as a convention — not just recording a one-time decision. Signal: if you'd want a future agent to do the same thing by default, it's a PATTERN. If you're recording why you made a specific choice, it's a DECISION. Examples of PATTERN: 'always XML-wrap injected content', 'use grep -iF for safe search'. Examples of DECISION: 'chose PostgreSQL over SQLite for this project', 'dropped filesystem scanning due to security risk'.\\\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n2. Optionally update the knowledge type descriptions in CLAUDE.md or hooks-system.md rule to add a 'When to use PATTERN vs DECISION' note.\n\n## Decisions\n\n### Locked\n- The knowledge entry itself must use PATTERN: type (meta-example)\n\n### Discretion\n- Whether to also ","source":"user","tags":["investigation","security","ui","bug","fix","pattern","convention","decision","rationale","constraint","env","postgres"],"ts":1773854303,"bead":"bd create --title=\"Fix PATTERN type gap: add guidance to use PATTERN: prefix explicitly\" --type=task --priority=4 --parent=bdcompound-7ji --description=\"## What\n\nAdd a PATTERN knowledge entry (and update CLAUDE.md guidance if appropriate) about when to use PATTERN: type explicitly vs burying patterns in DECISION/LEARNED entries.\n\n## Context\n\nThe retro found 0 explicit PATTERN: type entries this week despite 7 entries auto-tagged 'pattern' from content. The tags come from keyword detection in memory-capture.sh, but the entry type stayed 'decision' or 'learned'. This makes it harder to filter patterns specifically and defeats the purpose of having distinct knowledge types.\n\nThe six types each have a purpose:\n- LEARNED: insight from debugging/surprise behavior — one-time discovery\n- DECISION: what was chosen and why — specific choice with rationale\n- FACT: hard constraint, version req, environment detail — static truth\n- PATTERN: recurring convention or idiom — should be reused everywhere\n- INVESTIGATION: root cause analysis\n- DEVIATION: auto-fix outside bead scope\n\nWhen something is worth reusing as a convention (not just recording a one-time choice), it should be PATTERN.\n\n## What\n\n1. Add this as a PATTERN entry itself:\n\n\\`\\`\\`bash\nbdcompound-7ji\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n2. Optionally update the knowledge type descriptions in CLAUDE.md or hooks-system.md rule to add a 'When to use PATTERN vs DECISION' note.\n\n## Decisions\n\n### Locked\n- The knowledge entry itself must use PATTERN: type (meta-example)\n\n### Discretion\n- Whether to also update CLAUDE.md/hooks-system.md rule (assess if it adds clarity)\n\n## Testing\n- [ ] Entry is type 'pattern'\n- [ ] \\`recall.sh \\\"pattern type\\\"\\` returns this entry\n\n## Validation\n- [ ] Entry clearly distinguishes PATTERN from DECISION with concrete examples\n\n## Files\n- .beads/memory/knowledge.jsonl\n- .claude/rules/hooks-system.md (optional — only if adding a clarifying note)\n\n## Dependencies\nNone — but semantically follows bead 1 and 2 (do those first to practice the pattern)\""}
{"key":"fact-bd-create-title-document-chore-commit-convention-for-inf","type":"fact","content":"bd create --title=\"Document chore: commit convention for infra/config changes\" --type=task --priority=4 --parent=bdcompound-7ji --description=\"## What\n\nAdd a knowledge entry and optionally a CLAUDE.md note clarifying when to use chore: vs other conventional commit prefixes, specifically for the infra/config changes that tend to slip through as untyped.\n\n## Context\n\nThe CNAME commit this week was untyped: 'add CNAME for lavra.dev custom domain' should have been 'chore: add CNAME for lavra.dev custom domain'. Low stakes individually, but untyped commits break changelog generation and git log --grep filtering.\n\nThe ambiguous cases are:\n- DNS/domain changes → chore:\n- CI config changes → chore: or ci: (either fine, ci: preferred)\n- Dependency bumps → chore:\n- Gitignore/gitattributes → chore:\n- README-only → docs:\n- Script/tool additions → chore: (if not user-facing) or feat: (if user-facing)\n\n## What\n\nAdd a FACT entry:\n\n\\`\\`\\`bash\nConventional commit type for infra/config-only changes: use chore: for DNS records, CI config, gitignore, gitattributes, dependency bumps, non-user-facing scripts. Use ci: for CI-specific changes (either is fine but ci: is more discoverable). These are the cases most likely to slip through as untyped commits.\\\n\\`\\`\\`\n\nOptionally add a one-liner to CLAUDE.md global instructions if the untyped pattern recurs.\n\n## Decisions\n\n### Locked\n- Entry type: FACT (concrete rule, not a design choice)\n\n### Discretion\n- Whether to add to CLAUDE.md (only worth it if this is a recurring mistake)\n\n## Testing\n- [ ] Entry searchable via \\`recall.sh \\\"chore commit\\\"\\`\n\n## Validation\n- [ ] Tags include: git, commit, convention, chore\n\n## Files\n- .beads/memory/knowledge.jsonl\n- ~/.claude/CLAUDE.md (optional)\n\n## Dependencies\nNone\" --priority=4","source":"user","tags":["fact","test","fix","pattern","convention","decision","validation","config"],"ts":1773854340,"bead":"bd create --title=\"Document chore: commit convention for infra/config changes\" --type=task --priority=4 --parent=bdcompound-7ji --description=\"## What\n\nAdd a knowledge entry and optionally a CLAUDE.md note clarifying when to use chore: vs other conventional commit prefixes, specifically for the infra/config changes that tend to slip through as untyped.\n\n## Context\n\nThe CNAME commit this week was untyped: 'add CNAME for lavra.dev custom domain' should have been 'chore: add CNAME for lavra.dev custom domain'. Low stakes individually, but untyped commits break changelog generation and git log --grep filtering.\n\nThe ambiguous cases are:\n- DNS/domain changes → chore:\n- CI config changes → chore: or ci: (either fine, ci: preferred)\n- Dependency bumps → chore:\n- Gitignore/gitattributes → chore:\n- README-only → docs:\n- Script/tool additions → chore: (if not user-facing) or feat: (if user-facing)\n\n## What\n\nAdd a FACT entry:\n\n\\`\\`\\`bash\nbdcompound-7ji\n\\`\\`\\`\n\nOptionally add a one-liner to CLAUDE.md global instructions if the untyped pattern recurs.\n\n## Decisions\n\n### Locked\n- Entry type: FACT (concrete rule, not a design choice)\n\n### Discretion\n- Whether to add to CLAUDE.md (only worth it if this is a recurring mistake)\n\n## Testing\n- [ ] Entry searchable via \\`recall.sh \\\"chore commit\\\"\\`\n\n## Validation\n- [ ] Tags include: git, commit, convention, chore\n\n## Files\n- .beads/memory/knowledge.jsonl\n- ~/.claude/CLAUDE.md (optional)\n\n## Dependencies\nNone\" --priority=4"}
{"key":"pattern-catalog-drift-checks-belong-in-pr-ci-test-compatibility-job","type":"pattern","content":"Catalog drift checks belong in PR CI (test-compatibility job), not just release gates. Release-only checks are reactive — drift merges silently then blocks tagging. For a published marketplace, both ghost entries (in catalog, no file) AND missing entries (file exists, not in catalog) should be hard failures.","source":"user","tags":["pattern","test","react","job"],"ts":1773854670,"bead":"bdcompound-7ji"}
{"key":"learned-when-grepping-catalog-md-for-command-names-in-pre-release-ch","type":"learned","content":"When grepping CATALOG.md for command names in pre-release checks, constrain to table rows only (lines starting with |). Prose descriptions reference command names inline (e.g., 'Included in /lavra-design') and produce false positives if the whole document is searched.","source":"user","tags":["learned"],"ts":1773854671,"bead":"bdcompound-7ji"}
{"key":"fact-astro-6-glob-loader-normalizes-collection-entry-ids-lowerca","type":"fact","content":"Astro 6 glob loader normalizes collection entry IDs: lowercased + dots stripped (not just .md extension). Examples: AUTONOMOUS_EXECUTION.md → id: autonomous_execution. releases/v0.7.0.md → id: releases/v070 (dots stripped from the whole id path, not just extension). Section slug arrays in Doc.astro and index.astro must use lowercase IDs with underscores matching the loader output — hyphens and uppercase will not match. This is an Astro 6-specific behavior, undocumented, and different from Astro 5 (which only stripped .md). Discovered when sidebar showed empty Configuration and Releases sections after upgrade to Astro 6.","source":"user","tags":["fact","config"],"ts":1773854792,"bead":"bdcompound-7ji.1"}
{"key":"pattern-config-security-boundary-doctrine-for-lavra-1-storage-sep","type":"pattern","content":"Config/security boundary doctrine for Lavra. (1) Storage separation: .beads/config/ for settings, .beads/memory/ for knowledge — never mix them. merge=union in memory/ is for conflict-free JSONL merging; applying it to YAML/JSON config files corrupts frontmatter. (2) Agent context injection: always XML-wrap injected content with <untrusted-knowledge> tag + strip role prefixes (SYSTEM:/ASSISTANT:/[INST]) + strip Unicode bidirectional override chars (U+202A-U+202E, U+2066-U+2069) + strip null bytes before injection into system messages. (3) Safe search: use grep -iF (fixed-string, case-insensitive) not grep -i — prevents regex metacharacter injection when search terms come from bead titles or other user-controlled content. Known limitation: bidi-strip sed uses codepoint escapes that are not portable across all sed implementations — best-effort, not guaranteed. Newline-in-JSON gap: SANITIZED_KNOWLEDGE content is not newline-escaped before JSON embedding (unlike ESCAPED_STATE), so multi-line entries are best-effort safety only. Applies to: auto-recall.sh, any new hook reading .beads/ content into agent context.","source":"user","tags":["pattern","security","fix","config","rust"],"ts":1773854802,"bead":"bdcompound-7ji.2"}
{"key":"pattern-type-when-capturing-something-meant-to-be-reused-as-a-conven","type":"pattern","content":"type when capturing something meant to be reused as a convention — not just recording a one-time decision. The clearest signal: can you write it as a rule? 'When doing A, do B' = PATTERN. 'We chose A over B in this case because of C' = DECISION. LEARNED vs PATTERN overlap: LEARNED is for one-time discoveries that surprised you, not rules you would apply again. If you are filing a naming convention or architectural constraint as LEARNED, it is probably a PATTERN. Borderline example from this codebase: 'use beads- prefix for all workflow commands' is a PATTERN (a rule to follow every time). 'Renamed /deepen-plan to /beads-deepen for consistency' is a DECISION (a specific application of that pattern). One PATTERN entry replaces the need for many scattered DECISION entries that all reference the same underlying convention. This entry is itself a meta-example: it describes when to use PATTERN, and is filed as PATTERN so it is recalled when classifying future knowledge entries.","source":"user","tags":["pattern","fix","pattern","convention","decision","constraint","rest"],"ts":1773854810,"bead":"bdcompound-7ji.3"}
{"key":"fact-conventional-commit-type-for-infrastructure-and-config-only","type":"fact","content":"Conventional commit type for infrastructure and config-only changes: use chore: for DNS records (CNAME), CI config changes, gitignore/gitattributes, dependency bumps, and non-user-facing scripts/tools. Use ci: for CI-specific changes (either is acceptable, ci: is more discoverable). These are the cases most likely to slip through as untyped commits. Untyped commits break changelog generation and git log --grep filtering. Example: 'add CNAME for lavra.dev custom domain' should be 'chore: add CNAME for lavra.dev custom domain'.","source":"user","tags":["fact","convention","config"],"ts":1773854815,"bead":"bdcompound-7ji.5"}
{"key":"decision-both-ghost-commands-in-catalog-no-file-and-missing-comman","type":"decision","content":"Both ghost commands (in catalog, no file) and missing commands (file exists, not in catalog) are hard failures. Warn-vs-fail asymmetry was reviewed and rejected — for a published marketplace, undocumented commands are a defect, not a warning. Both directions exit 1.\" && \\\nFACT: CATALOG.md command extraction must be constrained to table rows (lines starting with |) using grep -E '^\\|' before extracting command names. CATALOG.md descriptions reference other commands inline (e.g., 'Included in /lavra-design') which produce false positives if the full document is searched.\" && \\\nCatalog accuracy check added to test-compatibility CI job (runs on every PR to main) rather than only verify-release (release-only). Drift that silently merges into main then blocks release tagging is prevented by catching it at PR time.","source":"user","tags":["decision","test","job"],"ts":1773854951,"bead":"bdcompound-7ji.4\nbdcompound-7ji.4\nbdcompound-7ji.4"}
{"key":"investigation-inventory-complete-lavra-writes-to-3-beads-subdirs-bead","type":"investigation","content":"Inventory complete. Lavra writes to 3 .beads/ subdirs: .beads/memory/ (knowledge.jsonl, recall.sh, knowledge-db.sh, session-state.md, .lavra-version, SQLite cache), .beads/config/ (lavra.json, project-setup.md, codebase-profile.md), .beads/retros/ (date.json snapshots). Hooks (auto-recall.sh, memory-capture.sh, provision-memory.sh) have hardcoded .beads/ paths throughout. Commands reference .beads/memory/ and .beads/config/ in their markdown bodies. Uninstaller does NOT clean up .beads/ data by design (preserves knowledge).\n\nFACT: beads backup/ dir (.beads/backup/) is owned by the beads CLI, not Lavra. Migration must not touch it.\n\nDECISION: Folder-level .lavra/.gitignore and .lavra/.gitattributes chosen over subdirectory-level. Cleaner — one file controls all ignore/merge rules for the directory. Previously .beads/memory/ had its own .gitattributes and .gitignore which was fragmented.\n\nDECISION: Hard recode .beads/ → .lavra/ (no dual-path fallback, no LAVRA_DIR env var). Migration script handles existing installs. Simpler hooks = fewer bugs.\n\nDECISION: Auto-migrate on install: copy + warn. Copy .beads/{memory,config,retros} to .lavra/. Leave .beads/ originals. Print warning: 'Old Lavra data preserved in .beads/ — safe to delete after verification'. No interactive prompt, no auto-delete.","source":"user","tags":["investigation","bug","decision","migration","config","env","cache"],"ts":1773857331,"bead":"bdcompound-63c\n\nbdcompound-63c\n\nbdcompound-63c\n\nbdcompound-63c\n\nbdcompound-63c"}
{"key":"decision-scope-mode-hold-plan-is-right-sized-6-phases-mechanic","type":"decision","content":"Scope mode: HOLD — plan is right-sized. 6 phases, mechanical path changes with clear verification. No scope expansion or reduction needed. Highest risk: Phase 4 (commands have .beads/memory/ in prose text, not just shell commands — grep verification is the right acceptance test).","source":"user","tags":["decision","test"],"ts":1773857347,"bead":"bdcompound-63c"}
{"key":"fact-gitattributes-and-gitignore-move-to-lavra-root-not-lav","type":"fact","content":".gitattributes and .gitignore move to .lavra/ root (not .lavra/memory/). Paths inside them use memory/ prefix: 'memory/knowledge.jsonl merge=union', 'memory/knowledge.db'. This is the key structural difference from the old setup.\n\n.lavra-version marker moves to .lavra/.lavra-version (root of .lavra/), not .lavra/memory/.lavra-version. auto-recall.sh must be updated to match in Phase 2.\n\nsubagent-wrapup.sh and knowledge-db.sh need ZERO changes. knowledge-db.sh is fully path-agnostic (all paths passed as parameters). subagent-wrapup.sh has no .beads/ refs.\n\n.lavra-version is at .lavra/.lavra-version (root), not .lavra/memory/. auto-recall.sh needs a LAVRA_DIR variable separate from MEMORY_DIR to read the version file correctly.\n\nPATTERN: Use cp -rn (no-clobber recursive) for migration to avoid overwriting if .lavra/ already exists. Migration must be idempotent.\n\n.beads/backup/ in lavra-ship.md must NOT be changed — it is owned by the beads CLI, not Lavra. All other .beads/ refs in commands should be updated.\n\nreleases/v0.7.0.md and other historical release notes must NOT be updated. They document what was true at that version. Only update current/active docs.\n\n772 total .beads/ references found across ~50 files. After all phases, final grep check should find zero non-exception results. Exceptions: .beads/backup/ in lavra-ship.md, migration detection code in installers, releases/v*.md historical notes.","source":"user","tags":["fact","fix","pattern","migration"],"ts":1773857634,"bead":"bdcompound-63c.2\n\nbdcompound-63c.2\n\nbdcompound-63c.1\n\nbdcompound-63c.1\n\nbdcompound-63c.3\n\nbdcompound-63c.4\n\nbdcompound-63c.5\n\nbdcompound-63c.6"}
{"key":"investigation-plan-deepened-with-research-from-7-agents-architecture-sec","type":"investigation","content":"Plan deepened with research from 7 agents (architecture, security, simplicity, deployment, data-migration, goal-verifier, performance). Key improvements: (1) Platform copies (opencode/, gemini/, cortex/) added to Phase 4 scope — 82+ files missed in original plan. (2) Migration function hardened: TARGET validation, SQLite exclusion, stale .gitattributes/.gitignore exclusion, post-copy line count check, idempotent re-run protection. (3) Migration smoke test (upgrade scenario) added to Phase 6. (4) check-memory.sh fallback hardcode at line 97 identified as easily-missed critical fix in Phase 2.\n\nFACT: cp -rn destination behavior: if destination dir does NOT exist, copies contents. If it DOES exist, copies into it. mkdir -p for .lavra/retros/ MUST precede cp -rn for retros migration. This is a known cp quirk that causes wrong-path bugs.\n\nFACT: Old .beads/memory/.gitattributes and .beads/memory/.gitignore MUST be excluded from migration copy. If they land in .lavra/memory/, they create redundant subdirectory-level attribute/ignore files that conflict with the new .lavra/ root-level files. Exclude them explicitly in the migration loop.\n\nPATTERN: git check-attr merge .lavra/memory/knowledge.jsonl is the correct post-install verification for merge=union. Must be in Phase 6 smoke test checklist.\n\nDECISION: Version 0.8.0 (minor bump). Structural directory change with migration is significant enough for minor version. Not a patch.","source":"user","tags":["investigation","security","test","ui","performance","bug","fix","pattern","architecture","decision","migration","validation","deploy","go"],"ts":1773858330,"bead":"bdcompound-63c\n\nbdcompound-63c\n\nbdcompound-63c\n\nbdcompound-63c\n\nbdcompound-63c"}
{"key":"learned-plan-review-found-1-migrate-beads-to-lavra-must-be-call","type":"learned","content":"Plan review found: (1) migrate_beads_to_lavra() must be called BEFORE provision_memory_dir() — reversed order causes idempotency guard to skip migration on empty knowledge.jsonl; (2) check-memory.sh line 38 and auto-recall.sh lines 32-38 both guard on .beads/ existence, must check .lavra/ for non-beads projects; (3) Phase 4 should re-run conversion scripts (bun run convert-opencode.ts) not manually sed platform copies — prevents drift\" 2>/dev/null","source":"user","tags":["learned","migration"],"ts":1773858889,"bead":"bdcompound-63c"}
{"key":"fact-scenario-2-migration-is-missing-a-negative-idempotency-tes","type":"fact","content":"Scenario 2 (migration) is missing a negative idempotency test: run installer a second time on a project that already has .lavra/memory/knowledge.jsonl with content — migration must be SKIPPED without overwriting existing data. Add this as Scenario 2b: run install.sh again on /tmp/test-lavra-migrate and verify .lavra/memory/knowledge.jsonl is unchanged (same line count as after first migration).\" 2>/dev/null","source":"user","tags":["fact","test","migration"],"ts":1773859126,"bead":"bdcompound-63c.6"}
{"key":"decision-applied-plan-review-feedback-14-recommendations-applied-acr","type":"decision","content":"Applied plan review feedback. 14 recommendations applied across 5 beads (bdcompound-63c.2, .1, .3, .4, .6). Key changes: (1) Phase 3 call order inverted — migrate_beads_to_lavra() before provision_memory_dir() in all installers; (2) Phase 2 scope expanded to fix check-memory.sh line 38 guard and auto-recall.sh lines 32-38 guard (both guard on .beads/ existence, silent failure for non-beads projects); (3) Phase 4 changed to re-run conversion scripts instead of manual sed on platform copies; (4) Security: auto-recall.sh bare heredoc JSON replaced with jq assembly, session-state.md gets sanitization pipeline; (5) Migration function simplified — removed path traversal re-validation, config exclusion logic, and post-copy line count check\" 2>/dev/null","source":"user","tags":["decision","security","fix","migration","validation","config"],"ts":1773859135,"bead":"bdcompound-63c"}
{"key":"decision-moved-all-lavra-management-to-folder-level-gitignore-and","type":"decision","content":"Moved all .lavra/ management to folder-level .gitignore and .gitattributes at .lavra/ root (not .lavra/memory/). Paths inside use memory/ prefix: 'memory/knowledge.jsonl merge=union', 'memory/knowledge.db'. .lavra-version moves to .lavra/.lavra-version. mkdir uses -m 700 for all subdirs. git add drops -f flag to respect user .gitignore.","source":"user","tags":["decision","fix"],"ts":1773859302,"bead":"bdcompound-63c.2"}
{"key":"decision-auto-recall-sh-guard-changed-from-if-beads-missing-exit","type":"decision","content":"auto-recall.sh guard changed from 'if .beads/ missing exit' to 'if both .beads/ AND .lavra/ missing exit'. Non-beads projects with .lavra/ can now use lavra. LAVRA_DIR separate var used for version file path at .lavra/.lavra-version vs MEMORY_DIR for .lavra/memory/. All bare heredoc JSON replaced with jq -cn assembly (H1 fix). session-state.md now sanitized and wrapped in untrusted-knowledge (M1 fix). CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR validation uses realpath canonical check AFTER early-exit guards (H3 fix + perf).","source":"user","tags":["decision","fix","validation","rust"],"ts":1773859434,"bead":"bdcompound-63c.1"}
{"key":"decision-added-migrate-beads-to-lavra-to-shared-functions-sh-share","type":"decision","content":"Added migrate_beads_to_lavra() to shared-functions.sh (shared by all 4 platform installers). Migration called BEFORE provision_memory_dir — order is load-bearing: provision creates empty knowledge.jsonl which would satisfy -s idempotency guard. Idempotency uses -s (non-empty check) not -f. Symlinks skipped with -L check. SQLite .db files and old gitconfig files excluded from memory/ copy.","source":"user","tags":["decision","migration","config"],"ts":1773859650,"bead":"bdcompound-63c.3"}
{"key":"fact-beads-lavra-compound-deepen-parallel-commands-in-opencode","type":"fact","content":"beads-*/lavra-compound/deepen/parallel commands in opencode/gemini/cortex platform dirs are stale files not regenerated by conversion scripts (no canonical sources). Had to apply sed directly after conversion script re-run. Conversion scripts only copy files that exist in plugins/lavra/commands/ — stale platform-only files persist until manually removed.","source":"user","tags":["fact"],"ts":1773859822,"bead":"bdcompound-63c.4"}
{"key":"fact-gitignore-and-gitattributes-move-to-lavra-root-not","type":"fact","content":".gitignore and .gitattributes move to .lavra/ ROOT — not .lavra/memory/. smoke tests in github-release.md and test scripts checking these files must use .lavra/.gitignore (not .lavra/memory/.gitignore). paths inside the files use memory/ prefix.","source":"user","tags":["fact","test","fix"],"ts":1773859999,"bead":"bdcompound-63c.5"}
{"key":"decision-bump-to-0-8-0-minor-version-structural-directory-chang","type":"decision","content":"Bump to 0.8.0 (minor version) — structural directory change from .beads/ to .lavra/ warrants minor bump per semantic versioning. All 5 smoke test scenarios pass: fresh install, migration, migration idempotency, .lavra/ gitignore warning, OpenCode and Gemini platform installers. pre-release-check.sh passes 19/19.","source":"user","tags":["decision","test","migration"],"ts":1773860155,"bead":"bdcompound-63c.6"}
{"key":"decision-changed-bd-show-json-to-long-in-single-bead-phase-1-l","type":"decision","content":"Changed bd show --json to --long in single-bead Phase 1. --long includes comments in readable format; --json requires jq parsing and subagents were not reading comments at all.","source":"user","tags":["decision","ui"],"ts":1774562888,"bead":"bdcompound-1na"}
{"key":"decision-testing-scope-branches-at-plan-time-not-implementation-time","type":"decision","content":"testing_scope branches at plan-time not implementation-time. The spec locks in test coverage targets before any code is written — changing the spec template is the correct intervention point. The implementing agent follows the spec.","source":"user","tags":["decision","test"],"ts":1774562946,"bead":"bdcompound-wlu"}
{"key":"decision-goal-verification-runs-per-wave-at-orchestrator-level-not-i","type":"decision","content":"Goal verification runs per-wave at orchestrator level, not inside subagent prompts. Subagents do self-review; orchestrator verifies the spec was actually met. Separation of concerns: subagent knows the code, orchestrator knows the bead spec.","source":"user","tags":["decision","go"],"ts":1774562955,"bead":"bdcompound-04f"}
{"key":"decision-used-bd-show-long-and-shell-text-parsing-awk-sed-rather","type":"decision","content":"Used bd show --long and shell text parsing (awk/sed) rather than --json + jq. --long output is stable and human-readable; jq parsing of nested JSON was causing orchestrator mistakes. The script is the reliability boundary.","source":"user","tags":["decision"],"ts":1774562973,"bead":"bdcompound-jvw"}
{"key":"decision-orchestrator-pre-processes-bead-context-via-extract-bead-con","type":"decision","content":"Orchestrator pre-processes bead context via extract-bead-context.sh before building subagent prompts. Subagents receive clean markdown, not raw JSON. The script is the reliability boundary — orchestrator mistakes from jq parsing are eliminated.","source":"user","tags":["decision","ui"],"ts":1774563039,"bead":"bdcompound-8or"}
{"key":"decision-parse-installer-args-shared-function-with-lavra-hooks-are","type":"decision","content":"parse_installer_args() shared function with LAVRA_HOOKS_ARE_GLOBAL flag. Cortex hooks are always global so the project-detection question is suppressed for that platform. Other platforms (claude, opencode, gemini) support per-project hooks so the question is shown.","source":"user","tags":["decision"],"ts":1774563500,"bead":"bdcompound-gnb.1"}
{"key":"pattern-script-resolves-library-path-relative-to-its-own-location-i","type":"pattern","content":"Script resolves library path relative to its own location: installed path (.claude/hooks/) tried first, source tree path (plugins/lavra/hooks/) tried second. This lets the script work in both dev and installed contexts without configuration.","source":"user","tags":["pattern","config"],"ts":1774563504,"bead":"bdcompound-jvw"}
{"key":"fact-goal-verifier-runs-per-bead-before-commits-in-phase-m8-crit","type":"fact","content":"goal-verifier runs per-bead before commits in Phase M8. CRITICAL failures (Exists/Substantive) reopen the bead via bd update --status open and exclude it from the wave commit. WARNINGs proceed but are noted in the wave summary.","source":"user","tags":["fact","go"],"ts":1774563512,"bead":"bdcompound-04f"}
{"key":"learned-bd-show-long-includes-comments-in-human-readable-format-in","type":"learned","content":"bd show --long includes comments in human-readable format in a single call. Subagents were reading descriptions but not comments, missing all INVESTIGATION/FACT/PATTERN findings from research agents. Switching from --json to --long closes this gap without any jq.","source":"user","tags":["learned","pattern"],"ts":1774563519,"bead":"bdcompound-1na"}
{"key":"learned-bsd-sed-silently-ignores-x-nnnn-unicode-escapes-bidi-s","type":"learned","content":"BSD sed silently ignores \\x{NNNN} unicode escapes — bidi strip in sanitize-content.sh is a complete no-op on macOS; use tr -d with ANSI-C \\$'\\\\uNNNN' quoting for portable unicode character deletion\nTITLE extracted from bd show output was not sanitized before injection into untrusted-knowledge block — all user-contributed fields (title, description, findings) must pass through sanitize_untrusted_content before prompt injection\nextract-bead-context.sh in scripts/ is never copied by any installer — scripts that need to run in target projects must be in plugins/lavra/hooks/ and listed in the hook copy loop of each platform installer\nset -euo pipefail + tr -d empty input can return exit 1 on BSD — sanitize_untrusted_content() pipeline must end with || true to prevent silent script death in command substitutions\nPhase M6 inline sanitization spec in lavra-work.md diverged from the shared sanitize-content.sh library immediately after extraction — command files that describe sanitization steps must reference the shared library rather than duplicating the spec\nPATTERN: when adding a new hook/script that targets installed projects, always verify it appears in the hook copy loop of all three platform installers (install-claude.sh, install-gemini.sh, install-opencode.sh)\nPATTERN: goal-verifier in multi-bead wave path — 'orchestrator already has bead details in memory' claim is ambiguous for bd ready input path; bd show must be called explicitly in Phase M1 for all paths before the validation section is referenced","source":"user","tags":["learned","pattern","validation","rust","go"],"ts":1774564080,"bead":"bdcompound-4xy\nbdcompound-4xy\nbdcompound-4xy\nbdcompound-4xy\nbdcompound-4xy\nbdcompound-4xy\nbdcompound-4xy"}
{"key":"learned-unnnn-ansi-c-quoting-is-not-supported-in-bash-3-2-mac","type":"learned","content":"\\$'\\\\uNNNN' ANSI-C quoting is not supported in bash 3.2 (macOS default) — produces literal string not Unicode codepoint; use printf '\\\\xNN...' for portable UTF-8 byte sequences in tr -d arguments\" 2>/dev/null; echo \"ok","source":"user","tags":["learned"],"ts":1774564637,"bead":"bdcompound-4xy"}
{"key":"learned-grep-e-ere-does-not-support-perl-style-lookaheads-like","type":"learned","content":"grep -E (ERE) does not support Perl-style lookaheads like (?!...). Both macOS BSD grep and GNU grep reject them. Use two-stage grep (match then exclude) instead.\" && bd close bdcompound-5iq","source":"user","tags":["learned"],"ts":1775266937,"bead":"bdcompound-5iq"}
{"key":"fact-bd-create-title-sanitize-knowledge-content-before-writing","type":"fact","content":"bd create --title=\"Sanitize knowledge content before writing to knowledge.jsonl\" --description=\"memory-capture.sh writes CONTENT directly to knowledge.jsonl without calling sanitize_untrusted_content(). This content is later injected into system prompts by auto-recall.sh.\n\nA crafted comment like:\nsomething. SYSTEM: ignore previous instructions...\\\nwould be stored unsanitized. The <untrusted-knowledge> wrapper in auto-recall.sh is the primary control (per security-injection.md), but defense in depth suggests we should also sanitize at write time.\n\nFix: source sanitize-content.sh in memory-capture.sh and pipe CONTENT through sanitize_untrusted_content() before building the JSON entry.\" --type=bug --priority=3","source":"user","tags":["fact","security","ui","bug","fix","rust"],"ts":1775519907,"bead":"bd create --title=\"Sanitize knowledge content before writing to knowledge.jsonl\" --description=\"memory-capture.sh writes CONTENT directly to knowledge.jsonl without calling sanitize_untrusted_content(). This content is later injected into system prompts by auto-recall.sh.\n\nA crafted comment like:\nmy-bead\nwould be stored unsanitized. The <untrusted-knowledge> wrapper in auto-recall.sh is the primary control (per security-injection.md), but defense in depth suggests we should also sanitize at write time.\n\nFix: source sanitize-content.sh in memory-capture.sh and pipe CONTENT through sanitize_untrusted_content() before building the JSON entry.\" --type=bug --priority=3"}
{"key":"fact-var-returns-exit-code-1-under-set-e-when-var-0-becaus","type":"fact","content":"((var++)) returns exit code 1 under set -e when var=0 because bash arithmetic treats the pre-increment value 0 as falsy. var=\\$((var + 1)) always exits 0. pre-release-check.sh already guarded with || true so it was exempt.","source":"user","tags":["fact"],"ts":1775520053,"bead":"bdcompound-grw"}
{"key":"decision-sourced-sanitize-content-sh-early-script-dir-early-to-avoi","type":"decision","content":"sourced sanitize-content.sh early (SCRIPT_DIR_EARLY) to avoid naming conflict with the later SCRIPT_DIR used by the sqlite block. Sanitization runs inline in the CONTENT extraction pipeline via | sanitize_untrusted_content | head -c 2048.","source":"user","tags":["decision","rust"],"ts":1775520063,"bead":"bdcompound-bup"}
{"key":"learned-test-the-coverage-in-the-trailing-operator-sed-oauth-wo","type":"learned","content":"# Test the || coverage in the trailing-operator sed\noauth works\" || handle_error' | sed -E 's/[\"'\"'\"'][[:space:]]*(2>&1|&&|\\||;).*$//\necho '---\noauth works\" || true' | sed -E 's/[\"'\"'\"'][[:space:]]*(2>&1|&&|\\||;).*$//","source":"user","tags":["learned","test","auth","error"],"ts":1775520229,"bead":"# Test the || coverage in the trailing-operator sed\nBD-001\necho '---'\nBD-001"}
{"key":"investigation-check-the-two-grep-pipeline-for-fact-style-bead-ids-learne","type":"investigation","content":"# Check the two-grep pipeline for FACT-style bead IDs\nLEARNED: something about facts\"' | \\\n  grep -E 'bd[[:space:]]+comments?[[:space:]]+add[[:space:]]+' | \\\n|LEARNED:|DECISION:|FACT:|PATTERN:|DEVIATION:)\necho '--- BEAD_ID extraction ---\nLEARNED: something about facts\"' | \\\n  grep -E 'bd[[:space:]]+comments?[[:space:]]+add[[:space:]]+' | \\\n|LEARNED:|DECISION:|FACT:|PATTERN:|DEVIATION:)' | \\\n  sed -E 's/.*bd[[:space:]]+comments?[[:space:]]+add[[:space:]]+([A-Za-z0-9._-]+)[[:space:]]+.*/\\1/","source":"user","tags":["investigation","pattern","decision"],"ts":1775520232,"bead":"# Check the two-grep pipeline for FACT-style bead IDs\nFACT-001\n  grep -E 'bd[[:space:]]+comments?[[:space:]]+add[[:space:]]+' | \\\n  grep -m1 -E '(INVESTIGATION:|LEARNED:|DECISION:|FACT:|PATTERN:|DEVIATION:)'\necho '--- BEAD_ID extraction ---'\nFACT-001\n  grep -E 'bd[[:space:]]+comments?[[:space:]]+add[[:space:]]+' | \\\n  grep -m1 -E '(INVESTIGATION:|LEARNED:|DECISION:|FACT:|PATTERN:|DEVIATION:)' | \\\n  sed -E 's/.*bd[[:space:]]+comments?[[:space:]]+add[[:space:]]+([A-Za-z0-9._-]+)[[:space:]]+.*/\\1/'"}
{"key":"learned-verify-the-stripping-behavior-more-carefully-the-in","type":"learned","content":"# Verify the || stripping behavior more carefully - the | in alternation is unanchored\n# Does | match the first pipe in ||?\nfoo\" || bd close BD-001' | sed -E 's/[\"'\"'\"'][[:space:]]*(2>&1|&&|\\||;).*$//\necho '---\n# And make sure closing quote IS being stripped when no trailing operator\nfoo\"' | \\\n  sed -E 's/.*bd[[:space:]]+comments?[[:space:]]+add[[:space:]]+[A-Za-z0-9._-]+[[:space:]]+[\"'\"'\"']//' | \\\n  sed -E 's/[\"'\"'\"'][[:space:]]*(2>&1|&&|\\||;).*$//' | \\\n  sed -E 's/[\"'\"'\"'][[:space:]]*$//","source":"user","tags":["learned"],"ts":1775520238,"bead":"# Verify the || stripping behavior more carefully - the | in alternation is unanchored\n# Does | match the first pipe in ||?\nBD-001\necho '---'\n# And make sure closing quote IS being stripped when no trailing operator\nBD-001\n  sed -E 's/.*bd[[:space:]]+comments?[[:space:]]+add[[:space:]]+[A-Za-z0-9._-]+[[:space:]]+[\"'\"'\"']//' | \\\n  sed -E 's/[\"'\"'\"'][[:space:]]*(2>&1|&&|\\||;).*$//' | \\\n  sed -E 's/[\"'\"'\"'][[:space:]]*$//'"}
{"key":"learned-check-if-is-correctly-handled-the-re-alternation-sh","type":"learned","content":"# Check if || is correctly handled - the | RE alternation should match first | in ||\n# What if the comment body itself contains a pipe?\nuse cat file | grep foo\"' | \\\n  sed -E 's/.*bd[[:space:]]+comments?[[:space:]]+add[[:space:]]+[A-Za-z0-9._-]+[[:space:]]+[\"'\"'\"']//' | \\\n  sed -E 's/[\"'\"'\"'][[:space:]]*(2>&1|&&|\\||;).*$//' | \\\n  sed -E 's/[\"'\"'\"'][[:space:]]*$//","source":"user","tags":["learned"],"ts":1775520240,"bead":"# Check if || is correctly handled - the | RE alternation should match first | in ||\n# What if the comment body itself contains a pipe?\nBD-001\n  sed -E 's/.*bd[[:space:]]+comments?[[:space:]]+add[[:space:]]+[A-Za-z0-9._-]+[[:space:]]+[\"'\"'\"']//' | \\\n  sed -E 's/[\"'\"'\"'][[:space:]]*(2>&1|&&|\\||;).*$//' | \\\n  sed -E 's/[\"'\"'\"'][[:space:]]*$//'"}
{"key":"learned-the-closing-quote-sed-requires-the-pipe-to-immediately-fol","type":"learned","content":"# The closing-quote sed requires the pipe to immediately follow the closing quote\nfoo\" | grep ... -- note space before pipe\nfoo\" | grep something' | \\\n  sed -E 's/.*bd[[:space:]]+comments?[[:space:]]+add[[:space:]]+[A-Za-z0-9._-]+[[:space:]]+[\"'\"'\"']//' | \\\n  sed -E 's/[\"'\"'\"'][[:space:]]*(2>&1|&&|\\||;).*$//' | \\\n  sed -E 's/[\"'\"'\"'][[:space:]]*$//\necho '---\n# What about || specifically\nfoo\" || true' | \\\n  sed -E 's/.*bd[[:space:]]+comments?[[:space:]]+add[[:space:]]+[A-Za-z0-9._-]+[[:space:]]+[\"'\"'\"']//' | \\\n  sed -E 's/[\"'\"'\"'][[:space:]]*(2>&1|&&|\\||;).*$//' | \\\n  sed -E 's/[\"'\"'\"'][[:space:]]*$//","source":"user","tags":["learned","ui"],"ts":1775520245,"bead":"# The closing-quote sed requires the pipe to immediately follow the closing quote\n# But what about: \"LEARNED: foo\" | grep ... -- note space before pipe\nBD-001\n  sed -E 's/.*bd[[:space:]]+comments?[[:space:]]+add[[:space:]]+[A-Za-z0-9._-]+[[:space:]]+[\"'\"'\"']//' | \\\n  sed -E 's/[\"'\"'\"'][[:space:]]*(2>&1|&&|\\||;).*$//' | \\\n  sed -E 's/[\"'\"'\"'][[:space:]]*$//'\necho '---'\n# What about || specifically\nBD-001\n  sed -E 's/.*bd[[:space:]]+comments?[[:space:]]+add[[:space:]]+[A-Za-z0-9._-]+[[:space:]]+[\"'\"'\"']//' | \\\n  sed -E 's/[\"'\"'\"'][[:space:]]*(2>&1|&&|\\||;).*$//' | \\\n  sed -E 's/[\"'\"'\"'][[:space:]]*$//'"}
{"key":"learned-bd-create-title-fix-sql-injection-risk-in-knowledge-db-sh","type":"learned","content":"bd create --title=\"Fix SQL injection risk in knowledge-db.sh kb_search() heredoc\" --type=bug --priority=1 --description=\"## Issue\nkb_search() in plugins/lavra/hooks/knowledge-db.sh builds an FTS5 MATCH expression by assembling \\$FTS_QUERY from user-controlled knowledge content, then interpolates it into an unquoted heredoc (<<SQL, not <<'SQL'). This means \\$FTS_QUERY and \\$TOP_N are shell-expanded before SQLite sees them.\n\nThe term extractor (grep -oE '\\b[a-zA-Z0-9_.]{2,}\\b') is the only thing currently preventing injection — one regex change away from breaking.\n\n## Severity\nP1 — The SQL heredoc is unquoted, meaning shell expansion applies. Stored knowledge content flows directly into the SQL statement.\n\n## Location\nplugins/lavra/hooks/knowledge-db.sh, kb_search() function, heredoc at lines ~147-154\n\n## Why This Matters\nIf a crafted knowledge entry with SQL metacharacters is stored (or if the term extractor is ever relaxed), the FTS5 MATCH expression could be broken out of, potentially executing arbitrary SQL against the knowledge database.\n\n## Fix\nChange <<SQL to <<'SQL_END' (quoted heredoc, no shell expansion) and pass \\$FTS_QUERY as a bound SQLite parameter, or use sqlite3 with a properly parameterized query:\n  sqlite3 \\\"\\$DB_FILE\\\" \\\"SELECT ... WHERE knowledge_fts MATCH ?\\\" \\\"\\$FTS_QUERY\\\n\n## Validation Criteria\n- [ ] kb_search() uses a quoted heredoc OR bound parameters — no string interpolation into SQL\n- [ ] A knowledge entry containing SQL metacharacters (', \\\", --, ;) can be stored and searched without error or injection\n\n## Testing Steps\ntest'; DROP TABLE knowledge_fts;--\\\n2. Run a recall search that would trigger kb_search()\n3. Verify the database is intact and no error is thrown\" 2>&1","source":"user","tags":["learned","test","database","ui","bug","fix","validation","error"],"ts":1775520342,"bead":"bd create --title=\"Fix SQL injection risk in knowledge-db.sh kb_search() heredoc\" --type=bug --priority=1 --description=\"## Issue\nkb_search() in plugins/lavra/hooks/knowledge-db.sh builds an FTS5 MATCH expression by assembling \\$FTS_QUERY from user-controlled knowledge content, then interpolates it into an unquoted heredoc (<<SQL, not <<'SQL'). This means \\$FTS_QUERY and \\$TOP_N are shell-expanded before SQLite sees them.\n\nThe term extractor (grep -oE '\\b[a-zA-Z0-9_.]{2,}\\b') is the only thing currently preventing injection — one regex change away from breaking.\n\n## Severity\nP1 — The SQL heredoc is unquoted, meaning shell expansion applies. Stored knowledge content flows directly into the SQL statement.\n\n## Location\nplugins/lavra/hooks/knowledge-db.sh, kb_search() function, heredoc at lines ~147-154\n\n## Why This Matters\nIf a crafted knowledge entry with SQL metacharacters is stored (or if the term extractor is ever relaxed), the FTS5 MATCH expression could be broken out of, potentially executing arbitrary SQL against the knowledge database.\n\n## Fix\nChange <<SQL to <<'SQL_END' (quoted heredoc, no shell expansion) and pass \\$FTS_QUERY as a bound SQLite parameter, or use sqlite3 with a properly parameterized query:\n  sqlite3 \\\"\\$DB_FILE\\\" \\\"SELECT ... WHERE knowledge_fts MATCH ?\\\" \\\"\\$FTS_QUERY\\\"\n\n## Validation Criteria\n- [ ] kb_search() uses a quoted heredoc OR bound parameters — no string interpolation into SQL\n- [ ] A knowledge entry containing SQL metacharacters (', \\\", --, ;) can be stored and searched without error or injection\n\n## Testing Steps\ntest-001\n2. Run a recall search that would trigger kb_search()\n3. Verify the database is intact and no error is thrown\" 2>&1"}
{"key":"investigation-bd-create-title-move-source-sanitize-content-sh-after-ear","type":"investigation","content":"bd create --title=\"Move source sanitize-content.sh after early-exit guards in memory-capture.sh\" --type=bug --priority=2 --description=\"## Issue\nIn plugins/lavra/hooks/memory-capture.sh, source \\\"\\$SCRIPT_DIR_EARLY/sanitize-content.sh\\\" runs before the early-exit guards (tool name check, command empty check, grep pattern checks). This means the file is sourced on EVERY PostToolUse:Bash call — including every git, grep, ls, test run, etc. — even though the sanitize function is only needed when a bd comments add with a knowledge prefix is detected (~1% of calls).\n\nThe script's own comment at line 26 acknowledges 'PostToolUse fires very frequently; this runs on ~1% of calls' as justification for placing the CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR validation after guards. The same logic should apply to the source.\n\n## Severity\nP2 — Hot path overhead. Adds ~3-5ms background CPU/IO overhead to every non-Bash tool call. Not blocking, but the fix is trivial and consistent with the established pattern in the file.\n\n## Location\nplugins/lavra/hooks/memory-capture.sh, lines 13-15\n\n## Fix\nMove the source to after the grep guards (or at minimum after the tool-name guard):\n\n  [[ \\\"\\$TOOL_NAME\\\" != \\\"Bash\\\" && \\\"\\$TOOL_NAME\\\" != \\\"bash\\\" ]] && exit 0\n  COMMAND=\\$(echo \\\"\\$INPUT\\\" | jq -r '.tool_input.command // empty')\n  [[ -z \\\"\\$COMMAND\\\" ]] && exit 0\n  echo \\\"\\$COMMAND\\\" | grep -qE 'bd\\\\s+comments?\\\\s+add\\\\s+' || exit 0\n|LEARNED:|...)' || exit 0\n  SCRIPT_DIR=\\\"\\$(cd \\\"\\$(dirname \\\"\\$0\\\")\\\" && pwd)\\\n  source \\\"\\$SCRIPT_DIR/sanitize-content.sh\\\n\nThis also eliminates the SCRIPT_DIR_EARLY / SCRIPT_DIR duplication (same fix as bead for SCRIPT_DIR unification).\n\n## Validation Criteria\n- [ ] source sanitize-content.sh appears after all grep guards in the file\n- [ ] test-features.sh Test 1 (DEVIATION: prefix capture) still passes\n- [ ] memory-capture.sh correctly sanitizes content when a knowledge comment is captured\n\n## Testing Steps\n1. Run scripts/test-features.sh — Test 1 should pass\n2. Verify with strace or timing that the source is not calle","source":"user","tags":["investigation","test","bug","fix","pattern","validation"],"ts":1775520368,"bead":"bd create --title=\"Move source sanitize-content.sh after early-exit guards in memory-capture.sh\" --type=bug --priority=2 --description=\"## Issue\nwith\n\nThe script's own comment at line 26 acknowledges 'PostToolUse fires very frequently; this runs on ~1% of calls' as justification for placing the CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR validation after guards. The same logic should apply to the source.\n\n## Severity\nP2 — Hot path overhead. Adds ~3-5ms background CPU/IO overhead to every non-Bash tool call. Not blocking, but the fix is trivial and consistent with the established pattern in the file.\n\n## Location\nplugins/lavra/hooks/memory-capture.sh, lines 13-15\n\n## Fix\nMove the source to after the grep guards (or at minimum after the tool-name guard):\n\n  [[ \\\"\\$TOOL_NAME\\\" != \\\"Bash\\\" && \\\"\\$TOOL_NAME\\\" != \\\"bash\\\" ]] && exit 0\n  COMMAND=\\$(echo \\\"\\$INPUT\\\" | jq -r '.tool_input.command // empty')\n  [[ -z \\\"\\$COMMAND\\\" ]] && exit 0\n  echo \\\"\\$COMMAND\\\" | grep -qE 'bd\\\\s+comments?\\\\s+add\\\\s+' || exit 0\n  echo \\\"\\$COMMAND\\\" | grep -qE '(INVESTIGATION:|LEARNED:|...)' || exit 0\n  SCRIPT_DIR=\\\"\\$(cd \\\"\\$(dirname \\\"\\$0\\\")\\\" && pwd)\\\"\n  source \\\"\\$SCRIPT_DIR/sanitize-content.sh\\\"\n\nThis also eliminates the SCRIPT_DIR_EARLY / SCRIPT_DIR duplication (same fix as bead for SCRIPT_DIR unification).\n\n## Validation Criteria\n- [ ] source sanitize-content.sh appears after all grep guards in the file\n- [ ] test-features.sh Test 1 (DEVIATION: prefix capture) still passes\n- [ ] memory-capture.sh correctly sanitizes content when a knowledge comment is captured\n\n## Testing Steps\n1. Run scripts/test-features.sh — Test 1 should pass\n2. Verify with strace or timing that the source is not called for non-matching Bash commands\" 2>&1"}
{"key":"learned-bd-create-title-add-operator-to-memory-capture-sh-trai","type":"learned","content":"bd create --title=\"Add || operator to memory-capture.sh trailing-operator sed strip\" --type=task --priority=3 --description=\"## Issue\nThe trailing-operator sed strip in memory-capture.sh:\n  sed -E 's/[\\\"'\\\\'']\\[[:space:]]*(2>&1|&&|\\\\||;).*\\$//\nhandles || (double-pipe) correctly only by accident — the single \\\\| branch matches the first | and .* consumes the rest. This works but is not self-documenting. A reader unfamiliar with this behavior would not know || is handled.\n\n## Location\nplugins/lavra/hooks/memory-capture.sh, COMMENT_BODY extraction pipeline\n\n## Fix\nAdd \\\\|\\\\| as an explicit alternation before \\\\|:\n  sed -E 's/[\\\"'\\\\'']\\[[:space:]]*(2>&1|\\\\|\\\\||&&|\\\\||;).*\\$//\n\n## Validation Criteria\nfoo\nfoo'\" 2>&1","source":"user","tags":["learned","fix","validation","rest"],"ts":1775520402,"bead":"bd create --title=\"Add || operator to memory-capture.sh trailing-operator sed strip\" --type=task --priority=3 --description=\"## Issue\nThe trailing-operator sed strip in memory-capture.sh:\n  sed -E 's/[\\\"'\\\\'']\\[[:space:]]*(2>&1|&&|\\\\||;).*\\$//'\nhandles || (double-pipe) correctly only by accident — the single \\\\| branch matches the first | and .* consumes the rest. This works but is not self-documenting. A reader unfamiliar with this behavior would not know || is handled.\n\n## Location\nplugins/lavra/hooks/memory-capture.sh, COMMENT_BODY extraction pipeline\n\n## Fix\nAdd \\\\|\\\\| as an explicit alternation before \\\\|:\n  sed -E 's/[\\\"'\\\\'']\\[[:space:]]*(2>&1|\\\\|\\\\||&&|\\\\||;).*\\$//'\n\n## Validation Criteria\ntest-001\ntest-001"}
{"key":"learned-var-under-set-e-was-missed-in-scripts-select-opencode","type":"learned","content":"((var++)) under set -e was missed in scripts/select-opencode-models.sh (starts at i=1 so does not crash immediately, but the pattern is wrong). Always grep the full repo after applying a set-e arithmetic fix, not just the reported files.\nsource of a shell library before early-exit guards adds overhead on the hot path of a PostToolUse hook. The script's own comment explained this pattern but the new source was added above the guards, violating it. Move library sources to after the primary grep guards.\nPATTERN: memory-capture.sh pipeline subshell in import-plan.sh -- PREV_BEAD mutations inside a piped while loop never propagate to the parent shell. Use process substitution (done < <(...)) instead of a pipeline when the loop must mutate caller variables.","source":"user","tags":["learned","crash","fix","pattern","model"],"ts":1775520426,"bead":"bdcompound-grw\nbdcompound-bup\nbdcompound-bup"}
{"key":"learned-knowledge-db-sh-kb-search-uses-an-unquoted-heredoc-sql","type":"learned","content":"knowledge-db.sh kb_search() uses an unquoted heredoc (<<SQL not <<'SQL') which allows shell expansion of \\$FTS_QUERY into the SQL statement. The term extractor is the only injection guard. Should use a quoted heredoc or bound parameters.","source":"user","tags":["learned"],"ts":1775520431,"bead":"bdcompound-bup"}
{"key":"fact-select-opencode-models-sh-had-i-at-line-101-inside-a-w","type":"fact","content":"select-opencode-models.sh had ((i++)) at line 101 inside a while loop under set -euo pipefail; replaced with i=\\$((i + 1)) to avoid exit-on-zero when i=0. This was the one file missed in the earlier PR #6 / bdcompound-grw fix pass.","source":"user","tags":["fact","fix","model"],"ts":1775520511,"bead":"bdcompound-a7o"}
{"key":"decision-fixed-sql-injection-in-kb-search-by-replacing-unquoted-her","type":"decision","content":"Fixed SQL injection in kb_search() by replacing unquoted heredoc (<<SQL) with sqlite3 bound parameter syntax -- FTS_QUERY is now passed as a positional ? arg after the SQL string, so it is never shell-expanded or interpolated into the query. TOP_N stays interpolated because it is validated as numeric (^[0-9]+$) earlier in the function, making it safe.","source":"user","tags":["decision","fix"],"ts":1775520527,"bead":"bdcompound-5bg"}
{"key":"learned-sqlite3-cli-accepts-bound-parameters-as-positional-arguments","type":"learned","content":"sqlite3 CLI accepts bound parameters as positional arguments after the SQL string: sqlite3 db.sqlite 'SELECT ... WHERE col MATCH ?' \\\"\\$VALUE\\\". This eliminates shell expansion of the variable into the SQL text. For LIMIT, a pre-validated numeric variable is safe to interpolate directly because there are no SQL-special characters in digits.","source":"user","tags":["learned"],"ts":1775520530,"bead":"bdcompound-5bg"}
{"key":"decision-moved-source-sanitize-content-sh-to-after-both-grep-guards-i","type":"decision","content":"Moved source sanitize-content.sh to after both grep guards in memory-capture.sh and consolidated SCRIPT_DIR_EARLY + SCRIPT_DIR into a single SCRIPT_DIR defined once post-guards. This avoids sourcing the file on every PostToolUse:Bash invocation (~3-5ms overhead) and only runs on the ~1% of calls that pass all guards.","source":"user","tags":["decision"],"ts":1775520543,"bead":"bdcompound-4v5"}
{"key":"fact-sanitize-untrusted-content-is-only-called-inside-the-prefi","type":"fact","content":"sanitize_untrusted_content() is only called inside the prefix loop at the CONTENT extraction line (line 66), so sourcing sanitize-content.sh immediately after the grep guards — before the CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR validation and MATCH_LINE extraction — guarantees the function is defined before it's needed with no functional behavior change.","source":"user","tags":["fact","fix","validation","rust"],"ts":1775520551,"bead":"bdcompound-4v5"}
{"key":"decision-fixed-by-converting-awk-grep-while-to-process","type":"decision","content":"Fixed by converting 'awk ... | grep ... | while' to process substitution form 'while ... done < <(awk ... | grep ...)'. This keeps the while loop body in the main shell so PREV_BEAD assignments persist across iterations. Process substitution is compatible with set -euo pipefail.","source":"user","tags":["decision","fix"],"ts":1775520607,"bead":"bdcompound-3rb"}
{"key":"learned-fact-select-opencode-models-sh-starts-i-1-so-i-does-n","type":"learned","content":"FACT: select-opencode-models.sh starts i=1 so ((i++)) does not crash on the first iteration, masking the bug. Still wrong — the pattern is inconsistent and will break if i is ever reset to 0.\nDECISION: Used sqlite3 bound-parameter syntax (positional ? argument) rather than switching to quoted heredoc. Quoted heredoc would prevent ALL variable expansion including TOP_N, requiring additional changes. Bound parameters are cleaner and more idiomatic.\nsqlite3 CLI supports parameterized queries: sqlite3 db.sqlite 'SELECT ... WHERE col MATCH ?' \\\"\\$VALUE\\\". The value is passed as a positional argument after the SQL string, not shell-expanded into it. TOP_N is safe to interpolate directly since it is validated as ^[0-9]+\\$ earlier.\nDECISION: Placed SCRIPT_DIR definition immediately after the grep guards (before CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR validation). This is slightly earlier than strictly necessary (sanitize_untrusted_content is only called in the prefix loop), but matches the natural boundary of the early-exit section and avoids interleaving setup code with logic.\nFACT: In bash, all stages of a pipeline run in subshells. PREV_BEAD mutations inside a piped while loop are lost on exit. Process substitution (done < <(cmd)) keeps the while loop in the main shell while still piping input from a subshell command.","source":"user","tags":["learned","ui","crash","bug","fix","pattern","model","decision","validation","rust"],"ts":1775520653,"bead":"bdcompound-a7o\nbdcompound-5bg\nbdcompound-5bg\nbdcompound-4v5\nbdcompound-3rb"}
{"key":"decision-used-tr-cd-a-za-z0-9-after-the-sed-extraction-to-make","type":"decision","content":"Used tr -cd 'A-Za-z0-9._-' after the sed extraction to make sanitization intent explicit at the use-site. The sed regex already constrains the character set, so tr is redundant in practice but serves as visible documentation of the invariant. A second empty-check guards against tr stripping the entire value.","source":"user","tags":["decision"],"ts":1775520680,"bead":"bdcompound-ap0"}
{"key":"decision-combined-sed-passes-2-and-3-into-a-single-alternation-s","type":"decision","content":"Combined sed passes 2 and 3 into a single alternation: 's/...(2>&1|\\|\\||&&|\\||;).*$|[\\\"'\\''][[:space:]]*$//' — also added explicit || before | per bdcompound-7wa. Both beads touch the same expression so combined into one atomic change.\" 2>/dev/null","source":"user","tags":["decision"],"ts":1775521891,"bead":"bdcompound-o5q"}
{"key":"fact-is-handled-correctly-by-the-old-single-branch-matche","type":"fact","content":"|| is handled correctly by the old single-| branch (| matches first pipe, .* eats rest), but adding it explicitly makes the intent self-documenting. Merged with o5q sed consolidation since both touch the same line.\" 2>/dev/null","source":"user","tags":["fact","rest"],"ts":1775521895,"bead":"bdcompound-7wa"}
{"key":"decision-chose-option-a-inline-over-b-c-d-file-indirection-via-ski","type":"decision","content":"Chose Option A (inline) over B/C/D. File indirection via skill files has a runtime failure mode on every non-project-install path (global Claude, Gemini, OpenCode, source repo). LLMs handle 1000-line prompts fine -- command size was never the root cause of review-skipping.\" 2>/dev/null\nReview language unified: /lavra-review ALWAYS runs. review_scope=full runs on all changes; review_scope=targeted runs only on P0/P1 or arch/security beads. Removed all 'self-review only' framing that implied self-review was a complete substitute for /lavra-review.\" 2>/dev/null\nFACT: test-features.sh Test 9 was failing because it checked lavra-work.md for Deviation Rules, goal-verifier, session-state, commit_granularity, and Locked/Discretion/Deferred -- all of which were in single-bead.md. Inlining fixed all 5 failures.\" 2>/dev/null","source":"user","tags":["decision","security","test","fix","go"],"ts":1775523307,"bead":"bdcompound-o3b\nbdcompound-o3b\nbdcompound-o3b"}
{"key":"investigation-cursor-sessionstart-hook-output-format-confirmed-uses-addit","type":"investigation","content":"Cursor sessionStart hook output format confirmed. Uses additional_context field (string) in stdout JSON, NOT hookSpecificOutput.systemMessage like Claude Code. Real-world example: printf '{\\\"additional_context\\\":\\\"...\\\"}'. This means knowledge injection IS possible via sessionStart.","source":"user","tags":["investigation"],"ts":1775528388,"bead":"bdcompound-com"}
{"key":"fact-cursor-hooks-json-lives-at-cursor-hooks-json-project-or","type":"fact","content":"Cursor hooks.json lives at .cursor/hooks.json (project) or ~/.cursor/hooks.json (user). Format: {version:1, hooks:{eventName:[{command:..., type:command, timeout:N}]}}. Event names are camelCase (sessionStart, afterShellExecution, subagentStop). No TeammateIdle equivalent exists in Cursor.","source":"user","tags":["fact","ui","timeout"],"ts":1775528393,"bead":"bdcompound-com"}
{"key":"fact-cursor-hook-event-mapping-to-claude-code-equivalents-sessio","type":"fact","content":"Cursor hook event mapping to Claude Code equivalents: sessionStart->sessionStart (same), afterShellExecution->PostToolUse:Bash, subagentStop->SubagentStop, stop->Stop. Cursor also has preToolUse, postToolUse, beforeShellExecution, subagentStart, afterFileEdit, beforeSubmitPrompt, preCompact, afterAgentResponse. NO TeammateIdle equivalent.","source":"user","tags":["fact","ui"],"ts":1775528397,"bead":"bdcompound-com"}
{"key":"fact-cursor-stdin-json-for-sessionstart-includes-session-id-is","type":"fact","content":"Cursor stdin JSON for sessionStart includes: session_id, is_background_agent, composer_mode + common fields: conversation_id, generation_id, model, hook_event_name, cursor_version, workspace_roots, user_email, transcript_path. Notably: cwd is NOT present (Claude Code sends cwd). Need workspace_roots[0] as equivalent.","source":"user","tags":["fact","ui","model"],"ts":1775528399,"bead":"bdcompound-com"}
{"key":"learned-cursor-hooks-auto-recall-must-use-workspace-roots-0-instead","type":"learned","content":"Cursor hooks auto-recall must use workspace_roots[0] instead of .cwd for project dir detection. auto-recall.sh reads cwd from stdin: CWD=$(echo \\\"$INPUT\\\" | jq -r '.cwd // empty'). For Cursor this must become: CWD=$(echo \\\"$INPUT\\\" | jq -r '.workspace_roots[0] // .cwd // empty'). This is the key adaptation needed in the hook.","source":"user","tags":["learned"],"ts":1775528403,"bead":"bdcompound-com"}
{"key":"decision-no-conversion-script-needed-for-cursor-cursor-uses-same-md","type":"decision","content":"No conversion script needed for Cursor. Cursor uses same .md format as Claude Code for commands and agents — but commands/agents are NOT installed (Cursor does not support slash commands or custom agent types). Only hooks and memory system are installed. This keeps install-cursor.sh simple: hooks + memory, nothing else.","source":"user","tags":["decision"],"ts":1775528408,"bead":"bdcompound-com"}
{"key":"fact-pattern-cursor-installer-follows-same-structure-as-install","type":"fact","content":"PATTERN: Cursor installer follows same structure as install-gemini.sh: banner, ownership check, hooks copy, memory provision, hooks.json write. Skip conversion step (no bun/typescript needed). ~150 LOC.\nCursor hooks.json version:1 format with camelCase events. Project hooks: .cursor/hooks.json. User hooks: ~/.cursor/hooks.json. Environment vars provided to scripts: CURSOR_PROJECT_DIR, CURSOR_VERSION, CURSOR_USER_EMAIL, CURSOR_TRANSCRIPT_PATH.","source":"user","tags":["fact","pattern","env","typescript"],"ts":1775528466,"bead":"bdcompound-cms\nbdcompound-cms"}
{"key":"investigation-cursor-subagents-docs-confirm-full-custom-agent-support-for","type":"investigation","content":"Cursor subagents docs confirm full custom agent support. Format: markdown with YAML frontmatter (name, description, model, readonly, is_background). File locations: .cursor/agents/ (project), ~/.cursor/agents/ (user), AND .claude/agents/ (Claude compatibility — Cursor reads these natively). This means Lavra agents work in Cursor without conversion if installed to .claude/agents/.\nFACT: Cursor plugin system has .cursor-plugin/plugin.json manifest. Supports: rules, skills, agents, commands, MCP servers, hooks. Components discovered automatically from default directories. Plugin installed to ~/.cursor/plugins/local/ for local testing. Marketplace at cursor.com/marketplace.\nDECISION: Cursor is a full port target (not memory-only). Agents work via .claude/agents/ compatibility. Commands need investigation (.cursor/ or .claude/ format?). install-cursor.sh scope expands to: hooks + memory + agents (via .claude/ compat) + optional plugin bundle. Update bead description to reflect this.","source":"user","tags":["investigation","test","model","decision"],"ts":1775528987,"bead":"bdcompound-88t\nbdcompound-88t\nbdcompound-88t"}
{"key":"investigation-opencode-agents-docs-confirm-full-custom-agent-support-open","type":"investigation","content":"OpenCode agents docs confirm full custom agent support (opencode.ai/docs/agents). Two definition methods: (1) opencode.json config under 'agent' key, (2) markdown files with YAML frontmatter in ~/.config/opencode/agents/ (global) or .opencode/agents/ (project). Fields: description, mode (primary/subagent/all), model, prompt, tools, permission, steps, temperature, hidden, color. The knowledge base entry 'OpenCode agents cannot be ported, has 4 predefined types only' is WRONG — that was stale/incorrect. OpenCode agents are nearly identical format to Cursor subagents.","source":"user","tags":["investigation","model","config"],"ts":1775529139,"bead":"bdcompound-88t"}
{"key":"investigation-learned-bd-prime-beads-global-sessionstart-hook-instructs","type":"investigation","content":"LEARNED: bd prime (beads global SessionStart hook) instructs agents to use 'bd remember' for persistent knowledge. This bypasses knowledge.jsonl entirely and won't be surfaced by auto-recall.sh. Fixed by adding explicit override in auto-recall.sh system message output.\nFACT: Cursor natively reads .claude/agents/ for Claude compatibility — Lavra agents work in Cursor without any conversion. Precedence when names conflict: .cursor/ > .claude/ > .codex/\nFACT: Cursor subagents are markdown files with YAML frontmatter (name, description, model, readonly, is_background). Invoked via /name or @name syntax or automatic delegation based on description field.\nFACT: OpenCode fully supports custom agents — the prior knowledge entry 'has 4 predefined types only' was wrong (verified opencode.ai/docs/agents Apr 2026). Markdown files in .opencode/agents/ with YAML frontmatter: description, mode (primary/subagent/all), model, prompt, tools, permission.\nCursor hooks.json uses camelCase events (sessionStart, afterShellExecution, subagentStop). sessionStart outputs additional_context field (confirmed via securityreviewai/securityreview-kit-cursor real-world example). Stdin uses workspace_roots[0] not cwd for project dir.","source":"user","tags":["investigation","security","fix","model"],"ts":1775529711,"bead":"bdcompound-88t\nbdcompound-88t\nbdcompound-88t\nbdcompound-88t\nbdcompound-88t"}
{"key":"learned-bd-prime-s-bd-remember-instruction-competes-with-lavra-s-k","type":"learned","content":"bd prime's 'bd remember' instruction competes with Lavra's knowledge.jsonl convention. Fixed in auto-recall.sh: convention note now appears in both first-run orientation and standard recall output, overriding bd prime before any command is invoked.","source":"user","tags":["learned","fix","convention"],"ts":1775529716,"bead":"bdcompound-cms"}
{"key":"decision-auto-recall-cursor-sh-is-15-loc-not-30-kept-minimal-p","type":"decision","content":"auto-recall-cursor.sh is ~15 LOC (not 30) — kept minimal per simplicity review. Uses .workspace_roots[0] // .cwd as fallback, no path allowlist (auto-recall.sh guards via .lavra/ existence check). Maps .hookSpecificOutput.systemMessage → additional_context using jq 'if ... then ... else empty end' to emit nothing rather than null on empty knowledge.\" 2>&1","source":"user","tags":["decision"],"ts":1775533520,"bead":"bdcompound-88t"}
{"key":"fact-memory-capture-sh-grep-pattern-changed-from-bd-s-comments","type":"fact","content":"memory-capture.sh grep pattern changed from 'bd\\s+comments?\\s+add\\s+' to '^[[:space:]]*bd[[:space:]]+comments?[[:space:]]+add[[:space:]]+' — the ^ anchor prevents false positives when .command from Cursor afterShellExecution contains a grep/cat of files that mention 'bd comments add' as examples.\" 2>&1","source":"user","tags":["fact","pattern"],"ts":1775533537,"bead":"bdcompound-88t"}
{"key":"learned-cursor-sessionstart-sends-workspace-roots-not-cwd-a-thi","type":"learned","content":"Cursor sessionStart sends workspace_roots[] not cwd -- a thin wrapper script is cleaner than patching auto-recall.sh directly. The wrapper injects cwd and maps hookSpecificOutput.systemMessage -> additional_context.\nFACT: Cursor afterShellExecution sends hook_event_name field but no tool_name field. The tool_name guard in memory-capture.sh must check hook_event_name to avoid silently skipping all Cursor memory capture.\nDECISION: Agents copy directly to .cursor/agents/ with no format conversion -- Cursor reads .md + YAML frontmatter natively, same as Claude Code.","source":"user","tags":["learned","decision"],"ts":1775533831,"bead":"bdcompound-88t\nbdcompound-88t\nbdcompound-88t"}
{"key":"pattern-karpathy-principle-maps-to-lavra-think-before-coding-la","type":"pattern","content":"Karpathy principle maps to lavra: Think Before Coding → lavra-plan clarification gate; Simplicity+Surgical → lavra-work Phase 2; Goal-Driven → goal-verifier (already exists)","source":"user","tags":["pattern","go"],"ts":1776198973,"bead":"lavra-850"}
{"key":"pattern-skills-x-references-directory-holds-assets-read-via-cat-by","type":"pattern","content":"skills/X/references/ directory holds assets read via cat by skill X — not invocable, no frontmatter, clearly scoped to owner","source":"user","tags":["pattern"],"ts":1776199239,"bead":"lavra-drj"}
{"key":"learned-recall-results-and-related-beads-in-multi-bead-subagent","type":"learned","content":"{RECALL_RESULTS} and {RELATED_BEADS} in multi-bead subagent template are not sanitized or wrapped in untrusted XML — auto-recall.sh wraps via sanitize_untrusted_content but Phase M6 inline recall does not. Pattern: all user-contributed content reaching subagent prompts must go through sanitize_untrusted_content + untrusted-knowledge XML wrapper.\nPATTERN: when extracting content from a monolithic command into skills, check every injection point — sanitization that was implicit (e.g. auto-recall.sh) does not automatically transfer to the new path\nsuccess_criteria and guardrails blocks in a router command duplicate the skill files it delegates to — create drift risk. Router should end at the routing decision, not carry completion criteria it never enforces.\nPATTERN: Think Before Planning / clarification gates in planning commands should sit above branching logic, not inside one branch — otherwise some input paths silently bypass the gate","source":"user","tags":["learned","pattern","decision","route","rust","go"],"ts":1776199595,"bead":"lavra-ceh\nlavra-ceh\nlavra-ceh\nlavra-ceh"}
{"key":"decision-added-untrusted-knowledge-wrapping-to-recall-results-and-rel","type":"decision","content":"added untrusted-knowledge wrapping to RECALL_RESULTS and RELATED_BEADS in both Phase M6 instructions and subagent-prompt.md template — defense in depth: orchestrator wraps before fill, template wraps the slot regardless","source":"user","tags":["decision","rust"],"ts":1776200456,"bead":"lavra-ceh.1"}
{"key":"pattern-all-user-contributed-content-reaching-subagent-prompts-must","type":"pattern","content":"all user-contributed content reaching subagent prompts must go through sanitize_untrusted_content + untrusted-knowledge XML wrapper — mirror auto-recall.sh lines 192-196 as the canonical pattern","source":"user","tags":["pattern","pattern","rust","go"],"ts":1776200459,"bead":"lavra-ceh.1"}
{"key":"decision-moved-think-before-planning-block-to-the-top-of-step-0-befo","type":"decision","content":"Moved Think Before Planning block to the top of Step 0 (before Step 0a), so it fires for all input paths — brainstorm and non-brainstorm alike. The block's core discipline (externalize interpretation, state assumptions, resolve ambiguity) applies equally before brainstorm detection begins, not just in the no-brainstorm fallback. Removed the duplicate block from Step 0d.","source":"user","tags":["decision","ui"],"ts":1776200471,"bead":"lavra-ceh.3"}
{"key":"decision-router-lavra-work-md-ends-at-process-no-trailing-su","type":"decision","content":"router (lavra-work.md) ends at </process> — no trailing success_criteria or guardrails. Skill files own those definitions. Cross-reference to ralph/teams removed from skill guardrails (irrelevant to subagents)","source":"user","tags":["decision","route"],"ts":1776200475,"bead":"lavra-ceh.2"}
{"key":"decision-added-header-comment-to-subagent-prompt-md-noting-it-is-not","type":"decision","content":"added header comment to subagent-prompt.md noting it is not a skill and that the untrusted XML wrappers are security boundaries not cosmetic formatting","source":"user","tags":["decision","security","rust"],"ts":1776200604,"bead":"lavra-ceh.6"}
{"key":"decision-wrapped-epic-plan-in-untrusted-knowledge-in-both-template-d","type":"decision","content":"wrapped EPIC_PLAN in untrusted-knowledge in both template (defense-in-depth) and Phase M6 instruction (pre-fill sanitization) — matches RECALL_RESULTS pattern added in lavra-ceh.1","source":"user","tags":["decision","pattern","rust"],"ts":1776200607,"bead":"lavra-ceh.4"}
{"key":"decision-coding-principles-moved-to-top-of-phase-2-governing-cons","type":"decision","content":"Coding Principles moved to top of Phase 2 — governing constraint should precede implementation preamble, not follow it","source":"user","tags":["decision","constraint","go"],"ts":1776200621,"bead":"lavra-ceh.5"}
